[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ I have been a professional player for more than 30 years, and it has been nearly a decade since I wrote a book on the Nimzo-Indian, so some of you may wonder why I haven't done a course like this before, why it has taken me so long.   Well, already in 2012 when my The Strategic Nimzo-Indian: A Complete Guide to the Rubinstein Variation came out with New in Chess, there were questions about a follow-up book on the Sämisch. Since the lines I recommended after 4.e3 sometimes already allowed for a transposition from the Rubinstein to the Sämisch. The reason I did not take on the task of expanding my proposed repertoire at the time was quite simply that some variations bothered me and posed problems which at the time I did not know how to solve in a way that offered White a satisfactory prospects.   Since then, both my accumulated experience and advances in computer engines have allowed me to make progress on those lines and produce a challenging repertoire for White. I hope you will like and enjoy the result. }
