[Black "The Extra Option 5...b6 6.Bg5!?"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 b6
{ This variation usually transposes to  5...Nc6  line. Whether it is better @@StartBracket@@for Black@@EndBracket@@ to start  5...b6  or  5...Nc6  is not easy to say.You will find @@StartBracket@@in your database@@EndBracket@@ more games to have had  5...b6  , but  5...Nc6  move order was the one chosen by the World champion Magnus Carlsen!In both cases, my mainline for White is  6.f3  and leads @@StartBracket@@should lead@@EndBracket@@ to the same line. White's main alternative to  6.f3  is  6.Bg5  . }
6. Bg5
{ Definitely an alternative for White! This move has been @@StartBracket@@just@@EndBracket@@ little played and Black can easily go wrong! }
6... h6 7. Bh4 Nc6
{ White has an interesting new idea @@StartBracket@@never tested before!@@EndBracket@@ probably leading to a promising pawn sacrifice. }
8. Qc2
{ White follows on his regular plan @@StartBracket@@pushing e4, taking space as fast as he can@@EndBracket@@, only willing to do it while keeping his f-pawn still on its initial square. }
8... Ba6 9. e4 { Delaying g5 pawn push is not a good idea for Black, as after }
9... Na5 10. Nf3
{ White threatens @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/p1pp1pp1/bp2pn1p/n7/2PPP2B/P1P2N2/2Q2PPP/R3KB1R w KQkq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  11.e5  , while Black does not have a good answer. }
10... g5
{ runs into tactical refutation.   10...Qc8  does not run into tactical refutation, but simply leads to a bad position for Black after  11.Nd2  Qb7  12.Be2  and Black simply does not have a sensible plan here, while  12...Qc6??  blunders into  13.e5  with  Bf3  to follow. }
11. Nxg5 hxg5 12. Bxg5 Rg8 13. h4
{ @@StartFEN@@r2qk1r1/p1pp1p2/bp2pn2/n5B1/2PPP2P/P1P5/2Q2PP1/R3KB1R w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  14.e5  is a threat, so Black needs to take on  g5  . }
13... Rxg5 14. hxg5 Ng8 15. f4
{ @@StartFEN@@r2qk1n1/p1pp1p2/bp2p3/n5P1/2PPPP2/P1P5/2Q3P1/R3KB1R w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  16.Rh8  is a threat, so Black needs to prepare long castle. }
15... Qe7 16. c5
{ This is Saemisch variation and White should not mind losing his c4-pawn. As a result of this pawn sacrifice, Black will not be able to castle to the queenside. For example  16...Bxf1  17.Kxf1  bxc5  18.Rh7  --  and Black cannot coordinate his pieces, while  19.g6  is a threat. White is much better. }
