1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 Nc6
{ One of Black's main lines against Saemisch and, among others, the one chosen by world champion Magnus Carlsen, who has played this line as Black on several occasions.Black keeps his pawn on c7 and intends to attack White's c4 pawn with the following plan: ...b6, ...Ba6, ...Na5  (to increase the pressure towards the c-pawn)   ...Qc8, ...Qb7, ...Qc6 and ...take the white c4 pawn!Achieving all this costs time, which will prove to be crucial! While Black is busy concentrating on White's  c4  pawn, White develops the initiative in the centre and on the kingside.The main line for White is  6.f3  followed by 7.e4 which takes space in the centre.However, White has two rarely played alternatives worth exploring and certainly a good surprise weapon!  6.e3  , played by the legendary seventh world champion Vasily Smyslov, and  6.Bg5 }
6. f3
{ White's little played alternative  6.e4  served Baadur Jobava well in his win against Magnus Carlsen at the 2014 Olympiad, but should not worry Black;  6...Nxe4  7.Qg4  now queens get off the board  7...f5  8.Qxg7  Qf6  9.Qxf6  Nxf6  Black is at least ok. White's c4-pawn remains a target, while a queen swap does not favor White. I do not recommend  6.e4  for White. }
6... b6
{ The most logical and best for Black, who wants to attack White's c4 pawn weakness as quickly as possible. }
7. e4 Ba6
{ The critical position for Black's 5...Nc6 line! White is now at the crossroads!This position has been played by many famous players and I don't think the best way for White to play has been established.All four main moves here  8.Bd3  ,  8.Bg5  ,  8.e5  and  8.Nh3  have their pluses and minuses. My choice is a personal one and I hope readers will like it.  With 8.Bd3 White plays a regular development move; by defending the e4-pawn, prepares to push f4, and is also able to defend the weakness of the c4-pawn with Qe2. }
8. Bd3 Na5 9. Qe2
{ Black here has an important strategic decision to make! To focus on White's c4-pawn weakness or to eliminate White's dark-squared bishop, thus limiting White's attacking arsenal. }
9... d6
{ We do not have many games here. White has in my opinion two promising options here. }
10. Nh3
{ Played at top level. White develops his knight and decides later on 'pawn moves'. }
10... Qd7
{ Black wants to use the standard plan to attack white's c4 pawn weakness and White prepares to protect it, if necessary, with the move Rb4. }
11. Rb1
{ We have very few games here. It is easy for Black to go wrong.The better-prepared player certainly has a @@StartBracket@@serious@@EndBracket@@ practical advantage! Many variants are tactical and require good calculation skills.The computer engine will start with a multiple zeros evaluation. In my analysis I have tried to combine logical human decisions @@StartBracket@@to reflect the direction in which the 'practical game' is likely to go@@EndBracket@@, while using the computational capacity of the silicon brain.Now probably the best thing for Black is to attack White's centre by delaying the castling decision. }
11... c5 12. Nf2
{ Preparing 13.e5, so that White's knight can quickly jump Ne4-Nd6  12.e5  is probably premature, as Black should not complain after  12...dxe5  13.dxe5  O-O-O!  14.Nf2  Ng8  when White cannot execute the desired Ne4-Nd6 jump. Since White is ready for 13.e5 ideas with Ne4 to follow, it looks sensible for Black to try to stabilize the centre. }
12... e5
{ In case of  12...O-O-O  13.O-O  White should be better, simply because his king is safer. And White needs to open up the center to make his bishop pair count! }
13. f4 O-O { May look logical for Black. } 14. fxe5 dxe5 15. dxe5 Ne8 16. O-O
Qe6
{ Black seems to be doing well... White has a bunch of weak pawns, which Black is about to start collecting. Unfortunately for Black, White is quick to develop a strong attack on Black's vulnerable king! }
17. Ng4 Bxc4 18. Rf5
{ Black does not have a good defence here. The combination of White's f-file pressure, Nh6+ or Nf6+ sacrificial motif does the job. Black's pieces don't coordinate well either. I'll give some lines that clearly show the problems Black is in. }
18... Bxd3 { Or  18...Rd8  19.Bxc4  Qxc4  20.Qe1  Rd3  21.Bg5  Rxc3  . } 19.
Qxd3 h5 { Looks like a smart defence but... the black king is vulnerable! } 20.
Nf6+ Nxf6 { 20...gxf6??  loses immediately to  21.Qg3++- } 21. exf6 Rad8
{ Now White still needs to be a bit precise with the execution, but the black king is in a mating net. }
22. Qg3 Rd1+ 23. Kf2 g6 24. Qe3
{ Black's only hope are some checks... but it does not really work @@StartBracket@@provided White is precise@@EndBracket@@. }
24... Qc4 25. Bd2
{ 25.Qh6??  is a blunder, as now Black saves the game  25...Qf1+  26.Kg3  Qe1+  27.Kh3  Rd3+  28.Rf3  Rxf3+  29.gxf3  Qf1+  30.Kg3  Qe1+  with perpetual check. }
