1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5 6. f3 Nc6 7. e4 d6
{ A flexible move. Black temporarily blocks White's e5 pawn thrust, while not allowing him to develop his knight on f2 through h3,   since  8.Nh3  fails to cause  8...e5  9.d5  Bxh3  10.dxc6  Bc8  with good play for Black.Black is also flexible with the decision on the position of his king.There are also some negative points: Black now needs more time to threaten to take White's c4-pawn, since there is control over a4 @@StartBracket@@Qa4+@@EndBracket@@.   7...O-O  is Black's other main option. White's main move here, based on the number of games played according to the database, is  8.Be3  In fact we have a good number of top players @@StartBracket@@like the 10th world champion Boris Spassky@@EndBracket@@ who support White's line  8.Be3  While the  8.Be3  line leads to interesting and complicated positions, it also has a huge amount of theory, and not everyone wants to spend hours learning!I myself spent quite a bit of time analysing  8.Be3  and, while finding interesting ideas, couldn't find an advantage for White.   White has two other interesting variations here that are worth exploring! My main line will be the much less played @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@  8.Ne2  , a move played by one of the Saemisch variation experts - Hungarian GM Ferenc Berkes. Another supporter of the  8.Ne2  line is the top Chinese GM Yu Yangui @@StartBracket@@well known for his excellent preparation of openings!@@EndBracket@@ Recently @@StartBracket@@although in a rapid internet game@@EndBracket@@ also the world champion Magnus Carlsen gave his seal of approval to the  8.Ne2  line!I also suggest exploring the almost unplayed @@StartBracket@@not at a high level anyway@@EndBracket@@  8.d5!?  move as White's alternative. }
8. Ne2
{ If Black tries to fix the centre by forcing White to push d5, White does not mind. White takes space and has advantage. We had one top level game in this variation. }
8... e5 9. d5 Na5 { Black is too slow to target white c4-pawn weakness. } 10.
Ng3 b6 { White should prepare the f4-push. } 11. Be2
{ Black has a few problems here:   a@@EndBracket@@ to attack White's c4-pawn weakness he needs to eliminate the possibility of a check on a4;   b@@EndBracket@@ any time the black bishop moves to a6-square, white knight can jump to f5 @@StartBracket@@Black does not really want to weaken himself with ...g6@@EndBracket@@. }
11... O-O 12. O-O Ba6 13. f4 { White will get strong attack on the kingside. }
