8. d5
{ So, let's explore White's alternative. This logical and direct move has been little played @@StartBracket@@at the time of this writing, only 16 games in my database!@@EndBracket@@. Where should Black go with his knight? In most of the games played, Black has responded by placing his knight on the square a5 aiming @@StartBracket@@as usual@@EndBracket@@ at the white c4-pawn. }
8... Na5 9. Bd3 b6
{ Black @@StartBracket@@as in most Saemisch lines@@EndBracket@@ wants to target White's c4-pawn weakness. White should, before taking any central action, finish his development. }
10. Ne2 Ba6
{ Due to the check on a4, Black still does not have a threat to grab white c4-pawn, so White castles. }
11. O-O
{ This is the eleventh move and a completely new position! Zero games in the database! Black can play several moves here @@StartBracket@@and the computer will give some lines around zero@@EndBracket@@, but it seems to me the most logical @@StartBracket@@anticipating the 'human run of play'@@EndBracket@@ Black trying to take the white c4-pawn. }
11... Nd7
{ Now Black has a threat to snatch the white pawn on c4, while not committing his king's position. }
12. Ng3 Bxc4 { Pawn grab is at least risky for Black. } 13. Bxc4 Nxc4 14. Qa4
Na5
{ White wants to jump with his knight to f5 and needs to provoke Black to push ...e5. }
15. Rd1 e5
{ White got what he wanted. White's knight now gets a great @@StartBracket@@monstrous!@@EndBracket@@ spot   15...Qe7?  protecting the d6-pawn leads to a terrible position for Black:  16.dxe6  fxe6  17.Bf4  . }
16. Nf5 Qf6
{ At first glance may look like: 'Ok,... White got his knight to f5, but Black is protecting everything and is a pawn up'. Well... White has a large, probably winning advantage here! }
17. h4 h6 { Energetic play is needed. } 18. g4
{ White now wins in a few moves. } 18... c4
{ If Black tries to fix the kingside with  18...g5  White simply plays  19.c4  The position will quickly collapse. Black is stuck all over the place.  White will play Bd2 @@StartBracket@@so Black has to worry about the queen side immediately@@EndBracket@@, Kg2 @@StartBracket@@since the white rooks are now connected@@EndBracket@@, hxg5 @@StartBracket@@opening the h-file@@EndBracket@@, Rh1... Black's situation is terrible - in computer language we are talking about more than plus four! }
19. g5 hxg5 { 19...Qg6??  20.h5 } 20. Bxg5 Qg6 21. Kf2 { With Rg1 to follow. }
