[Black "The Mainline 6...Ne8 7.e4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 O-O
{ This variation is usually related to the idea of moving  Nf6  , after White's  6.f3  , to the square e8 or h5. The most important principle for White is to follow his usual 'Saemisch plan' by building a strong centre. }
6. f3
{ Black's two main moves here are both knight jumps, moving from f6 either to e8 or h5.   Personally I think  6...Nh5  is the better move of the two. }
6... Ne8
{ Black can also play  6...d5  but this leads to different types of positions, where White usually continues  7.cxd5  exd5  8.e3  and we have transposed to positions analyzed in Chapters 8 and  9.   While  6...c5  7.e4  transposes @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/2PP4/P1P5/4PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  6.f3  Nc6  7.e4  O-O }
7. e4
{ This is White's most logical move and by far the main one. However, White has an interesting alternative! To better understand White's suggested alternative, let's try to understand Black's concept behind the strange looking 6...Ne8.In the  6...Ne8  line, Black wants to follow up on the plans seen in the 5...Nc6 @@StartBracket@@or 5...b6 @@EndBracket@@ line. Black has previously moved his knight from the e4-e5 thrust, eliminating the threat on the h4-d8 diagonal. Black's next step is to focus on the weakness of White's c4 pawn by following the plans seen in the 5...Nc6 line - so Black now wants ...Nc6; ...b6; ...Na5 and the capture of White's  c4  pawn. Black's problem is that this costs too much time.I think that if Black wants to follow this plan, he should opt for the original version of the variation 5...Nc6, 6...b6.My line comes from the game excellently played by one of Saemisch's experts, the Hungarian GM Ferenc Berkes. Berkes will focus on the attack on the king by showing that Black's idea of attacking White's  c4  pawn is too slow. I think White has several ways to gain an advantage against the 6...Ne8 line. }
7... b6 8. Bd3 Ba6 { White has a very specific attacking plan in mind. } 9. Nh3
Nc6 10. e5
{ White has a specific @@StartBracket@@and spectacular!@@EndBracket@@ sacrifice idea in mind.   10.Qe2  was also quite effective.  10...Qh4+  Black goes for winning a pawn, a snatch he should normally regret.  11.Nf2  Na5  12.O-O  Black has kept his pawn on  d7  , so now can go for the pawn, a pawn which White is happy to sacrifice!  12...Nd6  13.g3  Qe7  14.e5!  Ndxc4  Black has paid dearly for his love of material and is in terrible shape.  15.Ng4!   15.Qe4  f5  16.exf6  gxf6  and Black managed to survive in Fridman, D-Schlosser, P, Baden-Baden 2014.  15...d5   15...f5  loses to  16.exf6  gxf6  17.Bh6  Rf7  18.f4  White pushes f5 further opening Black's kingside.  16.Bh6!  gxh6  17.Nf6+  Kg7  18.f4!  Given all three black light pieces out of play, White actually makes an attack being two pieces up! }
10... Na5 { Now we can see the attacking idea that White has in mind. } 11. Ng5
f5 { If  11...h6  12.Nh7  White will be an exchange up in a better position. }
12. f4 { Black cannot keep the kingside closed with } 12... g6 13. h4 h5
{ because White 'breaks in' with } 14. g4 Ng7
{ 14...hxg4  15.h5  gxh5  16.Rxh5  Qe7  17.Ke2  and mate in a few moves. } 15.
gxh5 Nxh5 { How does White improve? The Standard Saemisch Rook Lift! } 16. Ra2
Bxc4 17. Bxc4 Nxc4 18. Rg2 { And Black cannot hold on the kingside. } *

