1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 O-O
{ This variation is usually related to the idea of moving  Nf6  , after White's  6.f3  , to the square e8 or h5. The most important principle for White is to follow his usual 'Saemisch plan' by building a strong centre. }
6. f3
{ Black's two main moves here are both knight jumps, moving from f6 either to e8 or h5.   Personally I think  6...Nh5  is the better move of the two. }
6... Ne8
{ Black can also play  6...d5  but this leads to different types of positions, where White usually continues  7.cxd5  exd5  8.e3  and we have transposed to positions anlayzed in Chapters 8 and  9.   While  6...c5  7.e4  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/2PP4/P1P5/4PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  6.f3  Nc6  7.e4  O-O }
7. e4
{ This is White's most logical move and by far the main one. However, White has an interesting alternative! To better understand White's suggested alternative, let's try to understand Black's concept behind the strange looking 6...Ne8.In the  6...Ne8  line, Black wants to follow up on the plans seen in the 5...Nc6 @@StartBracket@@or 5...b6 @@EndBracket@@ line. Black has previously moved his knight from the e4-e5 thrust, eliminating the threat on the h4-d8 diagonal. Black's next step is to focus on the weakness of White's c4 pawn by following the plans seen in the 5...Nc6 line - so Black now wants ...Nc6; ...b6; ...Na5 and the capture of White's  c4  pawn. Black's problem is that this costs too much time.I think that if Black wants to follow this plan, he should opt for the original version of the variation 5...Nc6, 6...b6.My line comes from the game excellently played by one of Saemisch's experts, the Hungarian GM Ferenc Berkes. Berkes will focus on the attack on the king by showing that Black's idea of attacking White's  c4  pawn is too slow. I think White has several ways to gain an advantage against the 6...Ne8 line. }
