f5 { If  11...h6  12.Nh7  White will be an exchange up. } 12. f4
{ White will play Qh5, so this move or the next, Black has to play move ...h6 }
12... h6 13. Qh5 { Black has to accept the sacrifice. } 13... hxg5 14. fxg5
{ @@StartFEN@@r2qnrk1/p1pp2p1/bp2p3/n3PpPQ/2PP4/P1PB4/6PP/R1B1K2R w KQ - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  15.g6  is a threat, so Black's next move is forced. }
14... g6 15. Qxg6+ Ng7 16. Qh6
{ @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/p1pp2n1/bp2p2Q/n3PpP1/2PP4/P1PB4/6PP/R1B1K2R w KQ - 2 16@@EndFEN@@  17.g6  is coming! }
16... Qe7 17. g6 Ne8
{ Black has prevented an immediate checkmate, but at what cost? White has removed the pawns in front of the black king and now brings more forces to the attack.Black's material advantage is of a temporary nature. He would like to return the material to improve his king's situation, but he has no good way to do so. }
18. O-O Qg7
{ White has played a brilliant game so far, but here more accurate than the continuation of the game was }
19. Qh5
{ White's bishop threatens to come to  h6  with devastating effect, so Black is forced to give his piece back.The game went  19.Qg5  and White went on to win in Berkes. F-Lysyj, I, Martuni 2009. }
19... Nf6 20. exf6 Rxf6
{ Material is now equal, but White has a winning attack. } 21. Bf4 Rxg6 22. Qe2
{ Black cannot survive here. The material is equal, Black has passive B+N @@StartBracket@@it will take time to put them into play@@EndBracket@@, Black's king is weak and White has an easy attack. }
22... d6 23. h4
{ And White is clearly better. The h-pawn will be disturbing the g6-Rook and Black's King is far from safe and Black doesn't have any counterplay. }
