1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 b6
{ This variation usually transposes to the  5...Nc6  line. Whether it is better @@StartBracket@@for Black@@EndBracket@@ to start  5...b6  or  5...Nc6  is not easy to say.You will find @@StartBracket@@in your database@@EndBracket@@ more games to have had  5...b6  , but  5...Nc6  move order was the one chosen by the World champion Magnus Carlsen!In both cases, my mainline for White is  6.f3  and leads @@StartBracket@@should lead@@EndBracket@@ to the same line. White's main alternative to  6.f3  is  6.Bg5  . }
6. Bg5
{ Definitely an alternative for White! This move has been @@StartBracket@@just@@EndBracket@@ little played and Black can easily go wrong! }
6... Bb7 { White is probably best advised to immediately take the space } 7. f3
{ Black's bishop is not really placed well on the b7-square @@StartBracket@@as it is not attacking the white c4-pawn@@EndBracket@@. Black now has a choice to push his d-pawn & correct White's pawn structure @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ or enter an inferior version of our regular lines }
7... d5 8. e3 Nbd7 { and now the most precise for White is } 9. cxd5 exd5 10.
Bd3
{ White has a good pawn structure and a bishop pair advantage. For Black, it is not easy to decide how to continue. If Black castles kingside, he will be just worse, while trying to be 'inventive' and castling queenside... does not really work. Play may continue }
10... Qe7
{ tactics are working for White here, so he does not need to spend an extra tempo defending his e3-pawn. }
11. Ne2 { White calmly develops the Knight. } 11... h6 12. Bf4 O-O-O
{ The most logical move, because the c7-pawn was hanging. } 13. Ng3 Qe6 14. Qc2
Kb8 { 14...g5?  15.Bf5  Qc6  16.Be5  Kb8??  17.Bxd7  Rxd7  18.Qf5+- } 15. h4
{ White stands clearly better. } *

