{ 8.f3  Ba6  9.e4  transposes to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/p1pp1ppp/1p2pn2/8/2PP4/P1P5/4PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.f3  Nc6  7.e4  Ba6  8.Bg5  h6  9.Bh4  line. In order not to get in @@StartBracket@@serious@@EndBracket@@ trouble Black needs to be precise. }
8... Bb7
{ Playable, but not the most principled for Black, as it does not target White's c4-weakness. We have a top level game here, and White's play can be improved on! }
9. Nd2 d6 10. e3
{ It is good to know that my Stockfish 12 is quite enthusiastic about pawn sacrifice, which is also a novelty  10.e4!?  e5  11.d5  Na5  12.c5!?  White's idea is often seen in similar positions. The sacrifice is 'intuitive' in its nature. White has sacrificed the pawn in order to destabilize black's centre.  12...dxc5  13.Be2 }
10... Ne7 11. f3 Ng6 12. Bf2 O-O 13. Bd3 Nd7
{ White has good kingside attacking prospects. } 14. h4 f5
{ We are following Eljanov-Jakovenko, Sochi 2006, and here White's play can be improved on with 'straightforward play'. }
15. h5
{ In the game itself, White executed a similar plan, but was less precise:  15.Qc2  Ne7  16.Rg1  c5  17.g4  cxd4  18.cxd4  fxg4  19.Rxg4  Nf6  20.Rg2  Rc8  -+ Black took over the initiative and went on to win in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@42@@EndBracket@@ Eljanov, P @@StartBracket@@2665@@EndBracket@@-Jakovenko, D @@StartBracket@@2675@@EndBracket@@ Sochi 2006. }
15... Ne7 16. Rg1
{ Simple and strong. The g4-push comes next; White gets a better version than the mentioned game. }
16... c5 { 16...Nf6  17.g4 } 17. g4 fxg4 18. fxg4
{ And here is good to mention that White recaptures with g5 to follow. } *

