[Round "?"]
[White "Ch.1: The Sideline 5...b6 with 7...d5"]
[Black "6.Bg5!? h6 with 7...Nc6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 b6
{ This variation usually transposes to  5...Nc6  line. Whether it is better @@StartBracket@@for Black@@EndBracket@@ to start  5...b6  or  5...Nc6  is not easy to say.You will find @@StartBracket@@in your database@@EndBracket@@ more games to have had  5...b6  , but  5...Nc6  move order was the one chosen by the World champion Magnus Carlsen!In both cases, my mainline for White is  6.f3  and leads @@StartBracket@@should lead@@EndBracket@@ to the same line. White's main alternative to  6.f3  is  6.Bg5  . }
6. Bg5
{ Definitely an alternative for White! This move has been @@StartBracket@@just@@EndBracket@@ little played and Black can easily go wrong! }
6... h6 7. Bh4 Nc6 8. Nf3
{ 8.f3  Ba6  9.e4  transposes to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/p1pp1ppp/1p2pn2/8/2PP4/P1P5/4PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.f3  Nc6  7.e4  Ba6  8.Bg5  h6  9.Bh4  line. In order not to get in @@StartBracket@@serious@@EndBracket@@ trouble Black needs to be precise. }
8... g5 9. Bg3 { In the case of } 9... d6
{ White prepares the central pawn advance and has the advantage. } 10. Nd2
{ White will push e4 and Black is best advised @@StartBracket@@as long as he can@@EndBracket@@ to take the white Bg3. }
10... Nh5 11. e4 Nxg3 12. hxg3
{ Black's best is to bring his knight to an 'usual square'. } 12... Na5 13. f4
{ Black needs to try to castle queenside; } 13... Qe7 14. Qh5 gxf4 15. gxf4 Bb7
{ If Black was to move and he was able to castle queenside, he would probably stand better. But it's White is to move. }
16. Qh4
{ This is not an easy choice for Black, as the pressure White has on the h-file is unpleasant. }
16... f6
{ 16...Qxh4  17.Rxh4  is just better for White. White easily defends his c4-pawn weakness, while he doubles on the h-file and Black has problems protecting his h-pawn. }
17. Qh5+ Kd7
{ White does not give Black time to consolidate. The position is dynamic and for both sides is easy to go wrong. }
18. d5 Rae8 19. Kf2 Kc8
{ 19...f5?  counterplay does not work due to the simple  20.Re1  White has a nice pawn sacrifice idea here! }
20. dxe6 Qxe6 21. Qf5 Bxe4
{ In the case of  21...Qxf5  22.exf5  we have a strange pawn structure, White having an advantage due to h-file pressure. }
22. Qxe6+ Rxe6 23. Re1 { Now Black needs to be precise! } 23... f5
{ White now gets dangerous passed pawns. } 24. Nxe4 fxe4
{ The rooks trade  24...Rxe4?  25.Rxe4  fxe4  makes White job only easier. }
25. g4 { Black needs to bring his knight back in play. } 25... Nb7 26. g5
{ Despite being a pawn down, White's passed pawns are securing him an advantage here. Black is fighting for a draw. }
