[Black "6.f3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 b6
{ This variation usually transposes to  5...Nc6  line. Whether it is better @@StartBracket@@for Black@@EndBracket@@ to start  5...b6  or  5...Nc6  is not easy to say.You will find @@StartBracket@@in your database@@EndBracket@@ more games to have had  5...b6  , but  5...Nc6  move order was the one chosen by the World champion Magnus Carlsen!In both cases, my mainline for White is  6.f3  and leads @@StartBracket@@should lead@@EndBracket@@ to the same line. White's main alternative to  6.f3  is  6.Bg5 }
6. f3
{ Straight forward and principled! White does have a reasonable alternative in  6.Bg5  6.e4  is just like in 5...Nc6 line is not dangerous for Black at all as queens will be swapped and Black will have excellent position after  6...Nxe4  7.Qg4  f5  8.Qxg7  Qf6  9.Qxf6  Nxf6 }
6... Ba6
{ 6...Nc6  7.e4  transposes to the@@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/2PP4/P1P5/4PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.f3  b6  7.e4 }
7. e4 d5
{ This line does not have a good reputation for Black, based on the Botvinnik-Tal World Championship game. Botvinnik actually did not play the best lines and even Tal's game can be improved, coming to a draw.White has a simple improvement of Botvinnik's game, getting a clear advantage.   7...Nc6  transposes to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/2PP4/P1P5/4PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nc6  6.f3  b6  7.e4  Ba6 }
8. cxd5 Bxf1 9. Kxf1 exd5
{ The critical moment. Here White can improve on Botvinnik's play! } 10. e5
{ The famous classic went  10.Bg5  h6  Now Black has problems because White's space advantage on the kingside counts! The position looks like a 'dream French' for White. White has excellent kingside attacking prospects. I will give some lines to support this verdict. }
10... Ng8 { Or  10...Nfd7  11.Ne2  Nc6  12.Nf4  Ne7  13.h4+- } 11. Ne2 Ne7 12.
Nf4
{ Black is in terrible trouble here. White easily develops the attack, while counterplay with }
12... c5
{ Does not really work for Black;   12...O-O  13.Nh5  c5  14.Bg5  looks fantastic for White. }
13. Nh5 Rg8 14. Kf2 Nbc6 15. Re1 cxd4 16. cxd4 Nf5 17. f4
{ Black cannot take the white pawn on d4, while White will start rolling his pawns. The black king is soon under terrible attack. }
17... Qd7 { Now White is simply rolling his pawns. } 18. Bb2 O-O-O
{ Or  18...Nfe7  19.g4+- } 19. g4 Nh4 20. f5
{ The white king is safe, while Black's is on the open c-file, on which White can immediately start his attacking operations.   The space advantage and Black's lack of counterplay give White a massive advantage. }
