[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch.2: The 5...Nc6 6.e3 Line"]
[Black "6.e3 with 6...O-O and 9...d6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 Nc6
{ One of Black's main lines against Saemisch and, among others, the one chosen by world champion Magnus Carlsen, who has played this line as Black on several occasions.Black keeps his pawn on c7 and intends to attack White's c4 pawn with the following plan: ...b6, ...Ba6, ...Na5  (to increase the pressure towards the c-pawn)   ...Qc8, ...Qb7, ...Qc6 and ...take the white c4 pawn!Achieving all this costs time, which will prove to be crucial! While Black is busy concentrating on White's c4 pawn, White develops the initiative in the centre and on the kingside.The mainline for White is  6.f3  followed by 7.e4 which takes space in the centre.However, White has two rarely played alternatives worth exploring and certainly a good surprise weapon!  6.e3  , played by the legendary seventh world champion Vasily Smyslov, and  6.Bg5 }
6. e3
{ It is not played often, it was tried long ago by Smyslov and it is definitely a good alternative for White.White will push e4, just like in our mainline, but will refrain from playing the move f3, giving himself in some lines a chance for a queen sortie with Qg4.The lines/positions we get are unexplored and certainly interesting for a player willing to take his opponent 'off the book' at a very early stage of the game.How should Black react? The most logical, and my mainline, is to follow his 'regular development strategy' in the variation 5...Nc6 then prepare ...Ba6, ...Nc4 thus attacking white's c4 pawn. }
6... O-O
{ Played by the Nimzo Indian expert Mark Taimanov in an old game against Vasily Smyslov, but it is questionable whether it is good for Black. Black castled early showing his hand regarding his king position and Smyslov easily and quickly developed a very strong attack. }
7. Bd3
{ Black now sticks to his original plan, but with his king already committed to the kingside White quickly gets a strong attack. }
7... b6 8. e4 Ne8 9. e5 d6 10. Nf3 dxe5 11. dxe5
{ Black must push his f-pawn, in this move or the next. } 11... f5
{ Black has closed the b1-h7 diagonal, so his king is, at least for a while, safe. Black's problem is the lack of space and a passive knight on e8. Thanks to the space advantage, White is better off. A logical continuation might be }
12. O-O Ba6 13. Qe2
{ Black's counterplay, as usual in most Saemisch lines, is based on White's c4-pawn weakness. This counterplay however is not really working for Black here. }
13... Na5 14. Bg5 Qd7 15. Rad1 Qf7
{ 15...Qa4?  is a mistake, as Black is reminded of his e6-pawn weakness after  16.Nd4 }
16. c5 { In the case of } 16... Bb7 { White plays } 17. Bb1
{ and places his bishop to a2-g8 diagonal. } 17... Bd5
{ Trying to stop White's plan, runs into } 18. Rxd5 exd5 19. Nd4
{ And Black's position collapses. } 19... Qg6 20. f4 bxc5 21. Nxf5 Rxf5 22. g4
*

