{ With similar ideas to  16...O-O-O  , which works less well for Black. } 17.
exf6 Rfe8 18. Be4
{ Black now needs quite a number of only moves, in order to avoid immediate resignation. }
18... g6 { 18...d5  loses to  19.Qh5+  and Black's king is in a mating net. }
19. Qc2 d5 20. cxd5 Qxd5 21. Kd1
{ Now Black needs to sacrifice another piece. } 21... d3 22. Qxc6 Qb3+ 23. Kd2
Rac8 { Black gets some of his sacrificed material back. } 24. Be5 Qxa3 25. Qd6
{ Now we get a more or less forced sequence of moves. } 25... Qa2+ 26. Rb2 Rc2+
27. Ke3 Rxb2 28. Bxb2 Qxb2 29. Kf3
{ After finding all those brilliant moves, Black still does not have sufficient compensation for a piece @@StartBracket@@ and the Black king is weak too!@@EndBracket@@. }
