[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch.4: The Mainline 5...c5 6.f3 Nc6 7.e4 with 7...O-O"]
[Black "Geirnaert - Sokolov, Brussels 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5
{ This is one of the mainlines of the Saemisch. In some opening manuals  5...c5  is even considered Black's best response.White has to choose between  6.e3  @@StartBracket@@and then push e4@@EndBracket@@ or a more direct  6.f3  , pushing e4 directly on the next move. Both lines have been played by many great players.I have analysed and played both and come to the conclusion that only  6.f3  gives White good prospects of gaining an opening advantage. }
6. f3 { In one rapid game I tried, playing Black } 6... b6 7. e4 O-O
{ This does not equalize for Black because the pin along the h4-d8 diagonal is unpleasant. }
8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4 d6 10. Bd3
{ An unpleasant pin on f6, while the center is not closed and Black does not want to weaken his kingside by playing ...g5. }
10... Nbd7
{ Now the best thing for White is simply to complete his development. } 11. Ne2
{ In my rapid game my opponent went for direct assault with  11.f4?!  At first glance, this looks promising for White, but Black has a strong resource in  11...cxd4!  12.cxd4  e5!  White went for the attack too early, his king is still on e1, and that matters @@StartBracket@@a lot!@@EndBracket@@.  13.fxe5  dxe5  14.Nf3  Now Black takes advantage of the fact that White's king is not yet castled.  14...exd4!  15.e5  Re8  16.O-O  Nxe5  White tries to keep his attack going, but it runs out of steam  17.Nxe5  Rxe5  18.Rxf6!  gxf6  19.Qf3  White's attack is less dangerous than it looks.  19...Re3!  20.Qxa8  Rxd3  21.Rf1  Qe8  Black was better and went on to win in Geirnaert, S - Sokolov, I, Brussels Rapid, 2018. }
11... e5 12. O-O
{ This is a good time to evaluate the position and see why White has better prospects.Black's knight on d7, instead of c6, has some disadvantages for Black:a@@EndBracket@@ White's d4 pawn is not attacked, so White is in no hurry to push to d5 and close the centre; b@@EndBracket@@ Black cannot go for his standard plan like ...Ba6, ...Na5 capturing White's c4 pawn.White keeps his pawn on d4, not closing the centre, and pushing the g-pawn @@StartBracket@@by resolving the h4-d8 pin@@EndBracket@@ weakens Black's king position and does not look interesting.Black has no active plan, while White can continue to improve his position by preparing to push f4 at the appropriate time. I will give a possible logical development of the game. }
12... Re8 13. a4
{ Such a move usually gives Black a headache in similar positions, as Black does not want to be worried about White pushing a5, while if Black pushes ...a5 himself, his b6-pawn might become a weakness. }
13... a5 14. Qd2
{ Black does not have an active plan and can finally try to solve the pin along the h4-d8 diagonal by bringing his knight to g6. }
14... Nf8
{ Now for White is the moment to strike! As usual @@StartBracket@@certainly when a piece sacrifice is involved@@EndBracket@@ accuracy is needed, but tactics work for White! }
15. f4 exf4 16. Nxf4
{ Black does not have much of a choice, but to accept White's piece sacrifice. }
16... g5 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. cxd5 gxh4 19. Qxh6
{ White has a winning attack here because the black king is weak, the black pieces coordinate poorly and black has no active defence, which means white actually has 'all the time in the world'.White improves his attack by doubling the rooks on the f-file; pushing the e5 pawn while bringing the Bd3 into the attack, is always a looming threat, as is bringing the rook on the h-file or the g-file.White has many ways. To give the reader an idea - the engine evaluation in this position is +4! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch.4: The Mainline 5...c5 6.f3 Nc6 7.e4 with 7...O-O"]
[Black "The Mainline 5...c5 6.f3 Nh5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5
{ This is one of the mainlines of the Saemisch. In some opening manuals  5...c5  is even considered Black's best response.White has to choose between  6.e3  @@StartBracket@@and then push e4@@EndBracket@@ or a more direct  6.f3  , pushing e4 directly on the next move. Both lines have been played by many great players.I have analysed and played both and come to the conclusion that only  6.f3  gives White good prospects of gaining an opening advantage. }
6. f3
{ In the case of  6.e3  comes a headache position.  6...Nc6  7.Bd3  O-O  8.Ne2  b6  9.e4  Ne8  10.O-O  Ba6  11.f4  f5  We have many high level @@StartBracket@@the highest@@EndBracket@@ games where this position has been tested.White failed to demonstrate any advantage along the way and often found himself in trouble; he lost because his initiative stopped, while the weakness of the  c4  pawn remained.I don't have any fresh ideas to bring to this line, I think Black is at least ok and so I suggest the reader play  6.f3! }
6... Nh5
{ A bad idea. Black creates the tactical threat of  7.--  Qh4+  that White easily solves, simply losing time for nothing.  ...Nh5 idea is playable for Black in 5...O-O 6.f3 Nh5 line, but here, this is not good, as White is quick in taking the centre. }
7. Nh3 { White will push e4, take space and have a clear advantage. } 7... f5
8. e4
{ Black can open up the f-file hoping to create a counterplay or even decide not to, but for the position's evaluation, it makes no difference - White is clearly better. }
8... O-O { White simply takes more space. } 9. e5
{ The position is easy to play for White. Black does not have counterplay and has a badly placed knight on h5. I will give a few more moves. }
9... d6 { White simply takes more space } 10. f4 g6 11. Be2
{ Black's counterplay lasts just a few moves. } 11... dxe5 12. fxe5 Qh4+ 13.
Nf2 cxd4 { And now Black is pushed to retreat. } 14. g3 Qd8 15. cxd4 Nc6 16.
Bb2
{ White has a large advantage here: the bishop pair, more space, central rolling pawns... }
