[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch.4: The Mainline 5...c5 6.f3 Nc6 7.e4 with 7...O-O"]
[Black "The Mainline 5...c5 6.f3 O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5
{ This is one of the mainlines of the Saemisch. In some opening manuals  5...c5  is even considered Black's best response.White has to choose between  6.e3  @@StartBracket@@and then push e4@@EndBracket@@ or a more direct  6.f3  , pushing e4 directly on the next move. Both lines have been played by many great players.I have analysed and played both and come to the conclusion that only  6.f3  gives White good prospects of gaining an opening advantage. }
6. f3 { In some games Black decided to try } 6... O-O 7. e4 d6
{ Better is  7...Nc6  transposing toour mainline 6...Nc6 7.e4 O-OWe have here a practical proof of a grandmaster game which clearly shows that the move 7...d6 cost Black important time @@StartBracket@@and he was late with his counterplay on the weakness of White's c4-pawn@@EndBracket@@. Let's look at this game. }
8. Bd3 Nc6 9. Ne2
{ Black dislikes both being pinned @@StartBracket@@with Bg5@@EndBracket@@ on the h4-d8 diagonal, and the f4/e5 pawn thrusts. So he takes prophylactic measures, as you often see in such Saemisch positions. }
9... Ne8 10. O-O b6
{ Black goes after White's c4-pawn weakness, but he is too late. } 11. f4 Ba6
12. f5
{ Straightforward and strong! Black has problems on the kingside and does not have the time to take White's c4-pawn. }
12... exf5 13. exf5
{ Black has to worry about the @@StartFEN@@r2qnrk1/p4ppp/bpnp4/2p2P2/2PP4/P1PB4/4N1PP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  14.f6  threat. }
13... h6
{ Just to point out, Black simply does not have the time for a 'pawn collection'  13...Na5?  14.f6!  White has a winning attack  14...Bxc4   14...Nxf6  runs under the deadly pin  15.Bg5  15.fxg7  Nxg7  16.Ng3  White's attack here plays by itself.White has a tremendous attack and the game can also be improved with }
14. Rf3
{ A typical rook lift. White will sacrifice his bishop on h6!In the actual game White sacrificed a pawn with  14.f6  typical for such positions: White's knight will come to f5 creating tactical threats.  14...Nxf6  15.Ng3  cxd4  16.Nf5!  White had a strong attack, worth more than the material he sacrificed. Black managed to survive and later draw in Khairullin, I - Kravtsiv, M Jerusalem, 2015. }
14... cxd4 15. Bxh6 { White needs to be precise, but the sacrifice works. }
15... gxh6 16. Rg3+ Kh8 17. Qc1
{ To prevent direct mate, Black loses his queen. } 17... Qf6
{ Or  17...Qh4  18.Rh3  Qxh3  19.gxh3  +-   17...Kh7??  runs into an immediate mate after  18.f6+ }
18. Nf4 Ne5 { Does not help Black. } 19. Nh5 Nxd3 20. Qd2 dxc3 21. Qe3
{ Black first loses his queen and then still gets mated. } *

