[White "Ch.4: The Mainline 5...c5 6.f3 Nc6 7.e4 with 7...O-O"]
[Black "The Mainline 5...c5 6.f3 Nc6 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5
{ This is one of the mainlines of the Saemisch. In some opening manuals  5...c5  is even considered Black's best response.White has to choose between  6.e3  @@StartBracket@@and then push e4@@EndBracket@@ or a more direct  6.f3  , pushing e4 directly on the next move. Both lines have been played by many great players.I have analysed and played both and come to the conclusion that only  6.f3  gives White good prospects of gaining an opening advantage. }
6. f3
{ In the case of  6.e3  comes a headache position.  6...Nc6  7.Bd3  O-O  8.Ne2  b6  9.e4  Ne8  10.O-O  Ba6  11.f4  f5  We have many high level @@StartBracket@@the highest@@EndBracket@@ games where this position has been tested.White failed to demonstrate any advantage along the way and often found himself in trouble; he lost because his initiative stopped, while the weakness of the  c4  pawn remained.I don't have any fresh ideas to bring to this line, I think Black is at least ok and so I suggest the reader play  6.f3! }
6... Nc6
{ In some opening manuals this line is even considered the main one in the Saemisch. I will give some of Black's alternatives. }
7. e4
{ Black has two main moves here, both played by many strong players.One is to castle, while another is to play  7...d6  , thus preventing White's 8.e5 and delaying the decision on the King's position.So I'll deal first with  7...O-O  and some sidelines. }
7... O-O { 7...d6  is, as mentioned, another Black's main line. } 8. e5
{ This position has been tested many times at the highest level. White has three main moves here:  1@@EndBracket@@  8.Be3  , played for example by Magnus Carlsen against Sergey Karjakin;  2@@EndBracket@@  8.d5  , played by the Chinese superstar Ding Liren;  3@@EndBracket@@ or the move I suggest the reader try in his/her own games:  8.e5 }
8... Ne8 9. f4 { Black can change the nature of the pawn structure opting for }
9... d5
{ This has been played recently in a high level internet blitz game. White should have advantage @@StartBracket@@bishop pair, space, potential kingside attack@@EndBracket@@; also, Black must be ready to sacrifice a pawn. }
10. Nf3 dxc4 11. Bxc4 cxd4 12. cxd4 b5 13. Bd3
{ Again @@StartFEN@@r1bqnrk1/p4ppp/2n1p3/1p2P3/3P1P2/P2B1N2/6PP/R1BQK2R w KQ - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  14.Bxh7  is a threat. }
13... h6 { 13...Bb7??  14.Bxh7++- } 14. O-O
{ Now Black must be ready to sacrifice a pawn. } 14... a6 15. Bc2
{ Leads to White's advantage as Black has problems protecting his kingside. }
15... Ne7 16. Qd3 g6 { Runs into } 17. f5 Nxf5 18. g4 Nh4 19. Bxh6
{ And Black is in a bad shape. } 19... Nxf3+ 20. Qxf3 Qxd4+ 21. Be3 Qxe5
{ Black's problem now is that he cannot prevent material losses. } 22. Rae1 Rb8
23. Ba7 Qc7 24. Bxb8 Qxb8 { Now White wins a very important pawn. } 25. Bxg6
Qa7+ 26. Rf2 { White has material advantage plus a strong attack. } *

