9... d6 10. Nf3 f5
{ Here White's play can be improved. White should go for an endgame! } 11. dxc5
{ In the game White continued with  11.exf6  Nxf6  12.Bd3  which at first glance looks good, but Black is quick with his counterplay.  12...e5!  13.fxe5  dxe5  14.dxe5  Qe8  15.O-O  Nxe5  with approximately equal position. The game later ended in a draw - Khismatullin, D-Rozum, I, Samara 2014. }
11... dxc5 12. Qxd8
{ I thought the queen's trade was 'better for White', but it wasn't until I started the engine that I realised how great it was! }
12... Nxd8 13. a4
{ Black has space problems, passive knights and his queenside pawns are weak. White has a large advantage. }
13... b6 14. a5 Nc7 15. Be3 Nc6
{ Now easiest for White is to connect his rooks and then open the a-file. } 16.
Be2 Rd8 { 16...Nxa5  17.Bxc5  only helps White. } 17. axb6 axb6 18. Kf2
{ Black's b6-pawn is weak, Black has no counterplay; White has a large advantage. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch.4: The Mainline 5...c5 6.f3 Nc6 7.e4 with 7...O-O"]
[Black "The Mainline 5...c5 6.f3 Nc6 #16"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5
{ This is one of the mainlines of the Saemisch. In some opening manuals  5...c5  is even considered Black's best response.White has to choose between  6.e3  @@StartBracket@@and then push e4@@EndBracket@@ or a more direct  6.f3  , pushing e4 directly on the next move. Both lines have been played by many great players.I have analysed and played both and come to the conclusion that only  6.f3  gives White good prospects of gaining an opening advantage. }
6. f3
{ In the case of  6.e3  comes a headache position.  6...Nc6  7.Bd3  O-O  8.Ne2  b6  9.e4  Ne8  10.O-O  Ba6  11.f4  f5  We have many high level @@StartBracket@@the highest@@EndBracket@@ games where this position has been tested.White failed to demonstrate any advantage along the way and often found himself in trouble; he lost because his initiative stopped, while the weakness of the  c4  pawn remained.I don't have any fresh ideas to bring to this line, I think Black is at least ok and so I suggest the reader play  6.f3! }
6... Nc6
{ In some opening manuals this line is even considered the main one in the Saemisch. I will give some of Black's alternatives. }
7. e4
{ Black has two main moves here, both played by many strong players.One is to castle, while another is to play  7...d6  , thus preventing White's 8.e5 and delaying the decision on the King's position.So I'll deal first with  7...O-O  and some sidelines. }
7... O-O { 7...d6  is, as mentioned, another Black's main line. } 8. e5
{ This position has been tested many times at the highest level. White has three main moves here:  1@@EndBracket@@  8.Be3  , played for example by Magnus Carlsen against Sergey Karjakin;  2@@EndBracket@@  8.d5  , played by the Chinese superstar Ding Liren;  3@@EndBracket@@ or the move I suggest the reader try in his/her own games:  8.e5 }
8... Ne8 9. f4
{ White's game is typical 'Saemisch style': taking space! We @@StartBracket@@at the time of this writing@@EndBracket@@ do not have many games in this line.I will follow, as the mainline, a relatively recent game played by two strong Russian grandmasters and also give alternatives.It is good to remember the idea of White's 8.e5! followed by  9.f4!  belongs to the legendary David Bronstein! }
9... d6 10. Nf3 f5
{ Here White's play can be improved. White should go for an endgame! } 11. dxc5
{ In the game White continued with  11.exf6  Nxf6  12.Bd3  which at first glance looks good, but Black is quick with his counterplay.  12...e5!  13.fxe5  dxe5  14.dxe5  Qe8  15.O-O  Nxe5  with approximately equal position. The game later ended in a draw - Khismatullin, D-Rozum, I, Samara 2014. }
11... dxc5 12. Qxd8
{ I thought the queen's trade was 'better for White', but it wasn't until I started the engine that I realised how great it was! }
12... Nxd8 13. a4
{ Black has space problems, passive knights and his queenside pawns are weak. White has a large advantage. }
13... a5 14. Be3
{ At first glance it may not seem so dramatic for Black, but the assessment is more than plus two! Space counts!Black has passive knights and White will continue to improve his position; the logic continuation may be }
14... b6 15. Be2 Bb7 16. Kf2 Bc6
{ Now White can play on both sides of the board. } 17. Rhb1 Ra6 18. Ng5
{ Black has to chase away the white knight and thus weaken himself on the kingside. }
18... h6 19. Rd1 Nc7 20. Nf3 Nf7 21. h4
{ White will continue with h5, Nh4, g4 while Black is a 'sitting duck'.White has a large advantage. }
