[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch.5: The Mainline 5...c5 6.f3 Nc6 7.e4 with 7...d6!?"]
[Black "The Alternative 8.d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5 6. f3 Nc6 7. e4 d6
{ A flexible move. Black temporarily blocks White's e5 pawn thrust, while not allowing him to develop his knight on f2 through h3, because  8.Nh3  fails to cause  8...e5  9.d5  Bxh3  10.dxc6  Bc8  with good play for Black.Black is also flexible with the decision on the position of his king.There are also some negative points: Black now needs more time to threaten to take White's c4-pawn, since there is control over a4 @@StartBracket@@Qa4+@@EndBracket@@.   7...O-O  is Black's other main option. White's main move here, based on the number of games played according to the database, is  8.Be3  In fact we have a good number of top players @@StartBracket@@like the 10th world champion Boris Spassky@@EndBracket@@ who support White's line  8.Be3  While the  8.Be3  line leads to interesting and complicated positions, it also has a huge amount of theory, and not everyone wants to spend hours learning!I myself spent quite a bit of time analysing  8.Be3  and, while finding interesting ideas, couldn't find an advantage for White.   White has two other interesting variations here that are worth exploring! My mainline will be the much less played @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@  8.Ne2  , a move played by one of the Saemisch variation experts - Hungarian GM Ferenc Berkes. Another supporter of the  8.Ne2  line is the top Chinese GM Yu Yangui @@StartBracket@@well known for his excellent preparation of openings!@@EndBracket@@ Recently @@StartBracket@@although in a rapid internet game@@EndBracket@@ also the world champion Magnus Carlsen gave his seal of approval to the  8.Ne2  line!I also suggest exploring the almost unplayed @@StartBracket@@not at a high level anyway@@EndBracket@@  8.d5!?  move as White's alternative. }
8. d5
{ So, let's explore White's alternative. This logical and direct move has been little played @@StartBracket@@at the time of this writing, only 16 games in my database!@@EndBracket@@. Where should Black go with his knight? In most of the games played, Black has responded by placing his knight on the square a5 aiming @@StartBracket@@as usual@@EndBracket@@ at the white c4-pawn. }
8... Ne5
{ It is possible, but I think the black players did not like this type of position after }
9. f4 Ng6
{ White no longer needs to worry about his c4-pawn becoming a target. } 10.
dxe6 fxe6 11. Bd3
{ This position @@StartBracket@@space, bishop pair@@EndBracket@@ looks better for White. }
