[White "Ch.5: The Mainline 5...c5 6.f3 Nc6 7.e4 with 7...d6!?"]
[Black "The Mainline 7...d6!? 8.Ne2 h6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5 6. f3 Nc6 7. e4 d6
{ A flexible move. Black temporarily blocks White's e5 pawn thrust, while not allowing him to develop his knight on f2 through h3,   since  8.Nh3  fails to cause  8...e5  9.d5  Bxh3  10.dxc6  Bc8  with good play for Black.Black is also flexible with the decision on the position of his king.There are also some negative points: Black now needs more time to threaten to take White's c4-pawn, since there is control over a4 @@StartBracket@@ Qa4+@@EndBracket@@.   7...O-O  is Black's other main option. White's main move here, based on the number of games played according to the database, is  8.Be3  .  In fact, we have a good number of top players @@StartBracket@@like the 10th world champion Boris Spassky@@EndBracket@@ who supports White's line  8.Be3  .  While the  8.Be3  line leads to interesting and complicated positions, it also has a huge amount of theory, and not everyone wants to spend hours learning!I myself spent quite a bit of time analysing  8.Be3  and, while finding interesting ideas, couldn't find an advantage for White.   White has two other interesting variations here that are worth exploring! My mainline will be the much less played @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@  8.Ne2  , a move played by one of the Saemisch variation experts - Hungarian GM Ferenc Berkes. Another supporter of the  8.Ne2  line is the top Chinese GM Yu Yangui @@StartBracket@@well known for his excellent preparation of openings!@@EndBracket@@ Recently @@StartBracket@@although in a rapid internet game@@EndBracket@@ also the world champion Magnus Carlsen gave his seal of approval to the  8.Ne2  line!I also suggest exploring the almost unplayed @@StartBracket@@not at a high level anyway@@EndBracket@@  8.d5!?  move as White's alternative. }
8. Ne2
{ We had an interesting high level rapid internet game, with Black unusually deciding to lose the time to prevent White's h4-d8 diagonal pin. }
8... h6 { Carlsen's mentioned game went } 9. Ng3 e5 10. dxc5
{ A well-known strategic idea, which does not work for White here!A better option for White was  10.Be3  However, Black has an equalizing idea that usually doesn't work, but here it does!  10...cxd4!  11.cxd4  exd4  12.Bxd4  Nxd4  13.Qxd4  This type of position is usually better for White, as the black d6-pawn weakness is more vulnerable than the White's one on  c4  . Here Black draws by forcing the transformation into a different pawn structure!  13...Qb6!  If White avoids the queen trade, he will have problems to castle.  14.Qxb6   White is not forced to go for an immediate queen trade, but the position looks equal after  14.Rd1  Ke7  15.Be2  Be6  White can improve the position of his knight  16.Nf1  Rhc8  17.Ne3  Chances are balanced.  14...axb6  Yes, Black's queenside pawns do not look great, but White himself has  c4  and  a3  weaknesses. The position is about equal and the draw is the most likely result. }
10... dxc5 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ Magnus now follows the strategic plan started with 10...dxc5: the white knight arrives at e3. }
12. Be2 b6 13. Nf1 Ba6 14. Ne3
{ This pawn structure is the product of White's strategic idea 10. dxc5.White doubles the c-pawns, but here it is also useful because the pawn on c3 stops Black's Nd4 jump.White will jump with his knight on d5 and if Black were to exchange the dominant knight White will continue with cxd5 improving his pawn structure.So why doesn't Carlsen's idea work? For this idea to work, White would need queens on the board. With queens on the board, it would have been difficult for Black to ignore White's knight on d5, whereas now he can! }
14... Na5 15. Kf2 Kc7 16. Nd5+
{ Black now simply ignores White, while White's c4-pawn weakness remains. }
16... Kb7 17. Rd1 Rad8 { White loses his c4-pawn without any compensation. }
18. Nxf6 Rxd1 19. Bxd1 gxf6 20. f4 Bxc4
{ Black had winning advantage, White saved the draw in Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2847@@EndBracket@@-Keymer, V @@StartBracket@@2591@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2021. }
