1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5 6. f3 Nc6 7. e4 d6
{ A flexible move. Black temporarily blocks White's e5 pawn thrust, while not allowing him to develop his knight on f2 through h3,   since  8.Nh3  fails to cause  8...e5  9.d5  Bxh3  10.dxc6  Bc8  with good play for Black.Black is also flexible with the decision on the position of his king.There are also some negative points: Black now needs more time to threaten to take White's c4-pawn, since there is control over a4 @@StartBracket@@ Qa4+@@EndBracket@@.   7...O-O  is Black's other main option. White's main move here, based on the number of games played according to the database, is  8.Be3  .  In fact, we have a good number of top players @@StartBracket@@like the 10th world champion Boris Spassky@@EndBracket@@ who supports White's line  8.Be3  .  While the  8.Be3  line leads to interesting and complicated positions, it also has a huge amount of theory, and not everyone wants to spend hours learning!I myself spent quite a bit of time analysing  8.Be3  and, while finding interesting ideas, couldn't find an advantage for White.   White has two other interesting variations here that are worth exploring! My mainline will be the much less played @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@  8.Ne2  , a move played by one of the Saemisch variation experts - Hungarian GM Ferenc Berkes. Another supporter of the  8.Ne2  line is the top Chinese GM Yu Yangui @@StartBracket@@well known for his excellent preparation of openings!@@EndBracket@@ Recently @@StartBracket@@although in a rapid internet game@@EndBracket@@ also the world champion Magnus Carlsen gave his seal of approval to the  8.Ne2  line!I also suggest exploring the almost unplayed @@StartBracket@@not at a high level anyway@@EndBracket@@  8.d5!?  move as White's alternative. }
8. Ne2
{ We have very few games here and a number of them are played on the internet, with a rapid time control.The theory will develop, as I think we will see 8.Ne2 line more. I will take as the mainline Black's usual plan - 'target and hopefully capture the white c4-pawn'. I will also give some of Black's alternatives. }
8... b6
{ Here we have an important moment: Ferenc Berkes' improvement on the old theory! }
9. Bg5
{ White pins the black knight, while freeing square c1 for his knight to take it to b3! By taking his knight to b3, White makes sure he doesn't lose the c4 pawn. }
9... h6 10. Bh4
{ The pin is unpleasant and Black has not yet committed his king to castle, so Black's decision is easy to understand. }
10... g5 11. Bf2
{ Now is the time for Black to follow the usual plan: 'attack and hope to take advantage of white's c4 pawn weakness'. }
11... Na5 12. Nc1 cxd4
{ Black is focused on c4-pawn, but the resulting position will favor White. }
13. cxd4 Ba6
{ This opening up of the position will not help Black, as White is just in time. }
14. Nb3 { It is perhaps good to mention that } 14... Nxc4 { is bad for Black. }
15. Nd2
{ Even if Black can manage to prevent losing a piece, he will get a very bad position. }
15... Qc8 16. Rc1 b5 17. h4
{ White can get his material back when he wants it, plus interest on his investment! }
