1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 O-O
{ This variation is usually related to the idea of moving Nf6, after White's 6.f3, to the square e8 or h5. The most important principle for White is to follow his usual 'Saemisch plan' by building a strong centre. }
6. Bg5
{ White has an interesting and very little played alternative.What is the natural reaction of man @@StartBracket@@all the more so in a rapid game@@EndBracket@@ who gets this position on the board for the first time? It could be: 'let's play 6...h6 first and then see...'.   Actually  6...h6?!  is already a mistake @@StartBracket@@!!@@EndBracket@@, since Black needs to have the white bishop hanging on g5, the moment Black makes the sortie with ...Qa5.I think Black really only has one way to draw here! }
6... c5
{ Black must be quick to use the white king on e1 and the white bishop on g5 and make possible the sortie of his queen on the a5-square. }
7. e3
{ This is a new concept for White; there is hardly any game, not a single GM game anyway. Black can draw, but he has to be precise. }
7... Qa5 { Black wins a pawn but falls under terrible attack. } 8. Bd3 Qxc3+
{ 8...cxd4  9.Bxf6  gxf6  10.exd4  Qxc3+  11.Kf1  is a transposition. } 9. Kf1
cxd4 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. exd4
{ My engine here is very enthusiastic about White; and 'humanly' the prospects for the attack also look excellent! I will give a few lines. }
11... Nc6 12. Ne2 Qa5 13. h4
{ The rook lift is a common plan in this type of position.   Black is not developed, has a weak king and can lose very quickly. }
13... d5 14. Rh3 dxc4 15. Rg3+ Kh8 { White has a mating attack. } 16. Qc1
{ Of course White does not need to take the pawn; instead he should prepare the pieces for the final assault. }
16... Qh5 17. Qf4 f5
{ Black has no other moves to defend f6, but now the queen is lost. } 18. Rg5
{ And Black will first lose his queen and then still get mated. } 18... Qh6 19.
Rg8+ Rxg8 20. Qxh6 cxd3 21. Nf4
{ And after Qf6 followed by Nh5 the game is over. } *

