1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 O-O
{ This variation is usually related to the idea of moving Nf6, after White's 6.f3, to the square e8 or h5. The most important principle for White is to follow his usual 'Saemisch plan' by building a strong centre. }
6. f3
{ Black's two main moves here are both knight jumps, moving from f6 either to e8 or h5.   Personally, I think  6...Nh5  is the better move of the two. }
6... Ne8 { An interesting alternative for White is } 7. a4
{ Another option for Black was to immediately play } 7... b6
{ and keep d6-square vacant for his Ne8 deployment. } 8. a5
{ It is not necessary for White, but it is logical to follow Mamedyarov's idea. }
8... Ba6 9. e4 Nc6 10. axb6 axb6 11. Bd3 Na5
{ We have a similar position to Mamedyarov's game, where Black, for tactical reasons, does not have a threat to take on c4. }
12. Nh3
{ Now Black can try to use the fact that the d6 square is free, an option Black did not have in the game, and take White's c4-pawn. }
12... Nd6
{ It does not hurt to mention  12...Nxc4??  blundering into  13.Rxa6  Rxa6  14.Bxc4   While after  12...Bxc4??  will follow  13.Rxa5  Bxd3  14.Rxa8  Qxa8  15.Qxd3 }
13. e5 { Black will regret having won a pawn. } 13... Ndxc4 14. O-O
{ Black has stupid knights who defend each other @@StartBracket@@and have nowhere to go@@EndBracket@@ while white quickly gets a strong kingside attack. The black king has no defenders @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@. }
