[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 O-O
{ This variation is usually related to the idea of moving Nf6, after White's 6.f3, to the square e8 or h5. The most important principle for White is to follow his usual 'Saemisch plan' by building a strong centre. }
6. f3
{ Black's two main moves here are both knight jumps, moving from f6 either to e8 or h5.   Personally, I think  6...Nh5  is the better move of the two. }
6... Ne8 { An interesting alternative for White is } 7. a4
{ An odd looking move, but played by the great Shakhriyar Mamedyarov and with a strong strategic idea behind it! As we'll see, White will open the a-file making it difficult @@StartBracket@@for tactical reasons@@EndBracket@@ for Black to take White's c4 pawn, while White launches his usual kingside attack. }
7... d6 8. e4
{ It is important for White to push a5 before Black stops him playing ...Nc6-Na5. }
8... b6 9. a5 Ba6 10. Bd3 Nc6 11. axb6 axb6
{ Mamedyarov gets exactly what he wanted: White gets a strong attack on the king, while Black @@StartBracket@@for tactical reasons related to the open a-file@@EndBracket@@ cannot pick up White's c4 pawn. }
12. Nh3 Na5 13. O-O c5
{ Again  13...Bxc4??  loses to  14.Rxa5  Bxd3  15.Rxa8  Qxa8  16.Qxd3  .   While  13...Nxc4??  blunders into  14.Rxa6  Rxa6  15.Bxc4  . }
14. d5
{ Black's position is already close to being lost. White has a strong attack on the kingside and doesn't even need to sacrifice a pawn for it; Black is passive and has no counterplay.White is already executing! Black realizes that he is actually two pieces short on the kingside and hopes to keep the position closed. }
14... e5 15. f4 exf4 16. Bxf4 f6
{ The attempt to fortify the position with ...f6 helps Black only temporarily. }
17. Nf2
{ With the idea of Nf2-g4-e3 f5. Nicely enough, the c4-pawn is still tactically defended.   17.Bg3  Bc8  18.Nf4 }
