{ This variation is usually related to the idea of moving Nf6, after White's 6.f3, to the square e8 or h5. The most important principle for White is to follow his usual 'Saemisch plan' by building a strong centre. }
6. f3
{ Black's two main moves here are both knight jumps, moving from f6 either to e8 or h5.   Personally I think  6...Nh5  is the better move of the two. }
6... Ne8 { An interesting alternative for White is } 7. a4
{ An odd looking move, but played by the great Shakhriyar Mamedyarov and with a strong strategic idea behind it! As we'll see, White will open the a-file making it difficult @@StartBracket@@for tactical reasons@@EndBracket@@ for Black to take White's c4 pawn, while White launches his usual kingside attack. }
7... d6 8. e4
{ It is important for White to push a5 before Black stops him playing ...Nc6-Na5. }
8... b6 9. a5 Ba6 10. Bd3 Nc6 11. axb6 axb6
{ Mamedyarov gets exactly what he wanted: White gets a strong attack on the king, while Black @@StartBracket@@for tactical reasons related to the open a-file@@EndBracket@@ cannot pick up White's c4 pawn. }
12. Nh3 Na5 13. O-O c5
{ Again  13...Bxc4??  loses to  14.Rxa5  Bxd3  15.Rxa8  Qxa8  16.Qxd3   While  13...Nxc4??  blunders into  14.Rxa6  Rxa6  15.Bxc4 }
14. d5
{ Black's position is already close to being lost. White has a strong attack on the kingside and doesn't even need to sacrifice a pawn for it; Black is passive @@StartBracket@@no counterplay@@EndBracket@@.White is already executing! Black realizes that he is actually two pieces short on the kingside and hopes to keep the position closed. }
14... e5 15. f4 Qe7 16. Ng5
{ Black cannot prevent the opening of the kingside. I will give some lines. }
16... exf4
{ If  16...h6  17.Nf3  Nf6  White continues with  18.fxe5  dxe5  19.Nh4  Bc8  20.Qe1 }
17. Bxf4 Nf6
{ Mamedyarov understands that his position is won and wants to take it home without further calculation. }
18. Qe2
{ More direct was  18.e5!  dxe5  19.d6  Qe8  20.Bg3  now 21.Rxf6 comes with devastating consequences  20...h6  21.Rxf6!  hxg5   if  21...gxf6  Black is in a mating net.  22.Nh7  Qe6  23.Qh5  Bxc4  24.Bf5  Black loses his queen, and gets mated too.  22.d7  Qe7  Black wants to have 23...e4 to prevent White's threat of Qh5 mate  23.Rxb6+  Black avoided getting mated, but lost decisive material. }
18... h6 19. Nf3 Rfe8
{ Mamedyarov calmly prepares the decisive thrust of the pawn e5. The knight on a5 and the bishop on a6 'sleep on the wrong side of the board'. }
20. Rae1 Nd7 21. e5 dxe5 22. Nxe5 Nxe5 23. Bxe5
{ Black king has no defenders. } 23... Qg5
{ White ends the game with an elegant finish. } 24. Qf3 Ra7 25. Bc7
{ 1-0 @@StartBracket@@25@@EndBracket@@ Mamedyarov, S @@StartBracket@@2742@@EndBracket@@-Alekseev, E @@StartBracket@@2708@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2008.Mamedyarov's @@StartFEN@@rnbqnrk1/pppp1ppp/4p3/8/2PP4/P1P2P2/4P1PP/R1BQKBNR w KQ - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.a4!?  idea is certainly worth giving it a try! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch.6: 5...O-O 6.f3 Ne8"]
[Black "The Mainline 6...Ne8 7.e4 with 9.f4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 O-O
{ This variation is usually related to the idea of moving Nf6, after White's 6.f3, to the square e8 or h5. The most important principle for White is to follow his usual 'Saemisch plan' by building a strong centre. }
6. f3
{ Black's two main moves here are both knight jumps, moving from f6 either to e8 or h5.   Personally, I think  6...Nh5  is the better move of the two. }
6... Ne8
{ Black can also play  6...d5  but this leads to different types of positions, where White usually continues  7.cxd5  exd5  8.e3  and we have transposed to positions anlayzed in Chapters 8 and  9.   While  6...c5  7.e4  transposes to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/2PP4/P1P5/4PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  6.f3  Nc6  7.e4  O-O  line }
7. e4
{ This is White's most logical move and by far the main one. However, White has an interesting alternative! To better understand White's suggested alternative, let's try to understand Black's concept behind the strange looking 6...Ne8.In the 6...Ne8 line, Black wants to follow up on the plans seen in the 5...Nc6 @@StartBracket@@or 5...b6@@EndBracket@@ line. Black has previously moved his knight from the e4-e5 thrust, eliminating the threat on the h4-d8 diagonal. Black's next step is to focus on the weakness of White's c4 pawn by following the plans seen in the 5....Nc6 line - so Black now wants ...Nc6; ...b6; ...Na5 and the capture of White's c4 pawn. Black's problem is that this costs too much time.I think that if Black wants to follow this plan, he should opt for the original version of the variation 5...Nc6, 6...b6.My line comes from the game excellently played by one of Saemisch's experts, the Hungarian GM Ferenc Berkes. Berkes will focus on the attack on the king by showing that Black's idea of attacking White's c4 pawn is too slow. I think White has several ways to gain an advantage against the 6...Ne8 line. }
7... b6 8. Bd3 Ba6 { White has a very specific attacking plan in mind. } 9. f4
{ Less spectacular than  9.Nh3  , but definitely leading to an opening advantage. }
9... Nc6 10. Nf3 Na5 11. Qe2
{ We can now transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/2PP4/P1P5/4PPPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c5  6.f3  Nc6  7.e4  O-O  8.e5  Ne8  9.f4  b6  line. }
11... c5
{ 11...Nb3  12.Rb1  Nxc1  13.Rxc1  is just better for White, please compare this position to the ones coming from 5...Nc6 line. }
12. e5 f5 13. d5 { We are now following Harikrishna-Werle, Nakhchivan 2003. }
13... d6 14. dxe6 Qe7 15. g4
{ White is better; we have transposed to the mentioned game. } *

