7... b6 8. Bd3 Ba6 { White has a very specific attacking plan in mind. } 9. Nh3
Nc6 10. e5
{ White has a specific @@StartBracket@@and spectacular!@@EndBracket@@ sacrifice idea in mind.   10.Qe2  was also quite effective.  10...Qh4+  Black goes for winning a pawn, a snatch he should normally regret.  11.Nf2  Na5  12.O-O  Black has kept his pawn on  d7  , so now can go for the pawn, a pawn which White is happy to sacrifice!  12...Nd6  13.g3  Qe7  14.e5!  Ndxc4  Black has paid dearly for his love of material and is in terrible shape.  15.Ng4!   15.Qe4  f5  16.exf6  gxf6  and Black managed to survive in Fridman, D-Schlosser, P, Baden-Baden 2014.  15...d5   15...f5  loses to  16.exf6  gxf6  17.Bh6  Rf7  18.f4  White pushes  f5  further opening Black's kingside.   16.Bh6!  gxh6  17.Nf6+  Kg7  18.f4!  Given all three black light pieces out of play, White actually makes an attack being two pieces up! }
10... Na5 { Now we can see the attacking idea that White has in mind. } 11. Ng5
f5 { If  11...h6  12.Nh7  White will be an exchange up in a better position. }
12. f4 { Black cannot keep the kingside closed with } 12... g6 13. h4 h5
{ because White 'breaks in' with } 14. g4 Ng7
{ 14...hxg4  15.h5  gxh5  16.Rxh5  Qe7  17.Ke2  and mate in a few moves. } 15.
gxh5 Nxh5 { How does White improve? The Standard Saemisch Rook Lift! } 16. Ra2
Bxc4 17. Bxc4 Nxc4 18. Rg2 { And Black cannot hold on the kingside. } *

