[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch.7: 5...O-O 6.f3 Nh5"]
[Black "8.e4 d6 9.Bd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 O-O 6. f3 Nh5
{ This knight jump has a more direct idea and also a better reputation than the  6...Ne8  line.At the time of this writing, there are more than 200 games in my database and Black has a score close to 60%!Many top players have opted for this line, including Magnus Carlsen. What does Black want? To slow down the typical Saemisch centre construction with White's e4 or to provoke White to risk doing so.At the moment Black threatens 7...Qh4+, so White's most logical move is to develop his knight and remove the threat at the same time. }
7. Nh3
{ Now Black pushes his f-pawn, aiming to prevent White from an easy e4-advance. }
7... f5
{ Now White is at the crossroads and the variation I am about to suggest is not the most played. I suggest White ignore the fact that he has been prevented from building the centre and play directly and aggressively. }
8. e4
{ Surprisingly, at least to me, players like Carlsen, Karjakin, and Mamedyarov did not choose this logical continuation, which seems to be the way for White to get an advantage in the opening. Also, we don't have many games, so it is likely that Black is already out of the book. Although I think White is objectively better, there are many lines where Black quickly enters a lost position while actually making seemingly logical moves.   8.e3  was played by Karjakin against Carlsen and is not dangerous at all. The main problem with  8.e3  is that it is too slow. By playing 6...Nh5, followed by 7...f5, Black is neglecting his development and must be punished by direct aggressive play.   8.Nf2  with the idea of pushing 9. e4 afterward makes more sense than  8.e3  but Black has a way to draw.   8.Bg5  is the most played move and makes a lot of sense. Black usually replies  8...Qe8  and now White should opt for the aggressive  9.g4!  We now have hair-raising complications, and the better-prepared player certainly has an advantage. My initial idea was to propose this as White's choice, but in the end, I decided against it because:a. yes, we get sharp tactical play, but I'm not sure White objectively has an advantage;b. in my suggested line  8.e4!  I think White simply has an opening advantage.Now Black is challenged to take e4, the most played move, or to ignore White's last move by pretending that 7...f5 was not aimed at stopping this move!So if Black gives up, White already has a certain psychological advantage! }
8... d6
{ Let's see the continuations in which Black ignores e4. White actually has a threat, that of pushing @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pppp2pp/4p3/5p1n/2PPP3/P1P2P1N/6PP/R1BQKB1R w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  9.e5!  After that Black has no good way to save his knight on h5!. Thus, only one sufficiently reasonable option remains. }
9. Bd3
{ As we shall see, Black's problem is that he cannot close the centre, since White either has the e5-pawn break or takes on f5. }
9... e5 { is indeed a blunder and loses material after } 10. exf5
{ White already has a winning advantage! We have one game here, that went as follows }
10... exd4
{ 10...Bxf5??  simply loses material after  11.Bxf5  Rxf5  12.g4  Qh4+  13.Nf2  . }
11. g4 Qh4+ 12. Nf2 Nf6 13. cxd4
{ White is a sound pawn up, while also having the better position. } 13... Re8+
14. Kf1 Nc6
{ White has several options here, but the one chosen in the game is logical and good. }
15. d5 Ne5 16. Bf4 Nfd7 17. Bg3
{ White has a winning advantage and went on to win in Yang, K @@StartBracket@@2360@@EndBracket@@-Sukandar, I  @@StartBracket@@2349@@EndBracket@@ Ho Chi Minh City, 2012. }
