8... d6
{ Let's see the continuations in which Black ignores e4. White actually has a threat, that of pushing @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pppp2pp/4p3/5p1n/2PPP3/P1P2P1N/6PP/R1BQKB1R w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  9.e5!  After that Black has no good way to save his knight on h5!. Thus, only one sufficiently reasonable option remains. }
9. Bd3 { Black can try to copy ideas from the 5...c5 6.f3 Nc6 line } 9... c5
10. O-O Nc6
{ The situation here is very different, however, as Black's kingside is compromised, so Black is unable to focus on White's c4 pawn. White has several good options here. }
11. exf5
{ The simplest.--- For readers willing to spend time memorising computer lines, I suggest having a look at  11.Bg5  Qa5  12.f4  Qxc3  13.d5!  Nd4  14.e5!  Stockfish is quite happy as White in this line, but I think  11.exf5  is more practical. }
11... exf5 12. Re1
{ Ra2 and Rae2 is coming and white will control the e-file. Black has a weak king and his Nh5 is also badly placed.You may wonder what happens if Black takes the pawn on d4? Well, let's see, because this is a typical Saemisch sacrifice. White willingly gives up his central pawn to open lines. }
12... cxd4 13. cxd4 Nxd4 14. Bf1
{ Here we have the typical situation after the sacrifice of a central pawn in the Saemisch. The black pieces are badly coordinated, the black king and the d6 pawn are weak, white has the Ra2-Rd2/e2 manoeuvre at his disposal. }
14... Ne6
{ Black for the moment prevents the a2-g8 diagonal tactics and wants ...Re8 followed by ...Nc7. The computer engine will tell you that White is winning, but I will give White 'human moves', so I will exclude the first three engine choices, just to show how strong White's compensation is.We start by moving the king for a possible check, which is a typical human player decision. }
15. Kh1
{ Your engine will give you the following line  15.Ra2  Re8  165.Rd2  Qb6+  17.Kh1  Nc7  18.Rxe8+  Nxe8  and it looks like Black is trading pieces while still a pawn up. But the black king is weak.  19.c5!  Qxc5  20.Rc2  Qa5  21.Bc4+  Kh8  22.Ng5  and we get many sharp engine lines, all of them winning for White.  22...h6  23.Nf7+  Kh7  24.g4! }
15... Re8 { Black must try to exchange rooks. } 16. Ra2 Nf8
{ Black has little choice but to develop he has to give up his extra pawn.Hanging the extra pawn with  16...Nc7  17.Rxe8+  Nxe8??  blunders into the prosaic  18.Qd5+  Kh8  19.Ng5  . }
17. Rxe8
{ Another move that is not one of the top three choices of the engine, but is still quite good.Supposedly best is  17.Rae2  Rxe2  18.Rxe2  . }
17... Qxe8 18. Rd2 { White gets his pawn back and has a clear advantage. } *

