{ This knight jump has a more direct idea and also a better reputation than the  6...Ne8  line.At the time of this writing, there are more than 200 games in my database and Black has a score close to 60%!.Many top players have opted for this line, including Magnus Carlsen. What does Black want? To slow down the typical Saemisch centre construction with White's e4 or to provoke White to risk doing so.At the moment Black threatens 7...Qh4+, so White's most logical move is to develop his knight and remove the threat at the same time. }
7. Nh3
{ Now Black pushes his f-pawn, aiming to prevent White from an easy e4-advance. }
7... f5
{ Now White is at the crossroads and the variation I am about to suggest is not the most played. I suggest White ignore the fact that he has been prevented from building the centre and play directly and aggressively. }
8. e4
{ Surprisingly, at least to me, players like Carlsen, Karjakin, Mamedyarov did not choose this logical continuation, which seems to be the way for White to get an advantage in the opening. Also, we don't have many games, so it is likely that Black is already out of the book. Although I think White is objectively better, there are many lines where Black quickly enters a lost position while actually making seemingly logical moves.   8.e3  was played by Karjakin against Carlsen and is not dangerous at all. The main problem with  8.e3  is that it is too slow. By playing 6...Nh5, followed by 7...f5, Black is neglecting his development and must be punished by direct aggressive play.   8.Nf2  with the idea of pushing 9. e4 afterwards makes more sense than  8.e3  but Black has a way to draw.   8.Bg5  is the most played move and makes a lot of sense. Black usually replies  8...Qe8  and now White should opt for the aggressive  9.g4!  We now have hair-raising complications, and the better-prepared player certainly has an advantage. My initial idea was to propose this as White's choice, but in the end, I decided against it because:a. yes, we get sharp tactical play, but I'm not sure White objectively has an advantage;b. in my suggested line  8.e4!  I think White simply has an opening advantage.Now Black is challenged to take e4, the most played move, or to ignore White's last move by pretending that 7...f5 was not aimed at stopping this move!So if Black gives up, White already has a certain psychological advantage! }
8... Nc6 { Is not a good idea to ingore white central pawns. } 9. e5
{ Black is in a bad situation, Nh5 is terribly placed and Black can choose between getting a bad position or going for an incorrect piece sacrifice. }
9... f4
{ Can lead to a good tactical chance for White; White has other ways to win, but why not do it with an attack! }
10. g4 fxg3 11. Bg5 Qe8 12. f4
{ One of Black's many problems is the bishop on c8 and the rook on a8 which are totally out of play. }
12... h6 13. Be2 Qg6 14. Bd3 Qf7 15. hxg3 { The g-file is now open. } 15...
Nxg3 16. Rg1 Nf5 17. Bf6 Nce7 18. Ra2
{ Time for our typical rook lift. White has many ways to win this position, but the following line demonstrates well the horrible situation Black finds himself in:  18...Kh8  19.Rxg7!  Nxg7  20.Rg2  Rg8  21.Ng5  Qe8  22.Rh2  and Black is mated. }
