[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch.8: 5...c5 6.f3 d5"]
[Black "6...d5 with 8.e3 Qc7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5
{ Black can also play  5...d5  , however after  6.cxd5  exd5  7.e3  c5  8.Bd3  O-O  9.Ne2  b6  it is only White who can choose between different possibilities. He can enter our mainline with  10.O-O  Ba6  11.f3  , or opt for a different pawn structure with  11.dxc5  bxc5  12.Bxa6  Nxa6  13.c4  or finally play  11.Bxa6  Nxa6  12.Qd3  Nc7  13.dxc5  bxc5  14.c4  . }
6. f3 d5 7. cxd5 exd5 8. e3
{ Black here has a couple of sidelines, all leading to White's advantage, which I will point out. }
8... Qc7
{ Perhaps the most important sideline. Black seems to stop White's natural development, as  9.Bd3  loses material after  9...cxd4  followed by 10...Qc3Many grandmasters have opted for  9.Ne2  or  9.Ra2  here, both deviating from White's more natural development. White here is well advised to allow Black to execute his threat. }
9. Bd3
{ At the time of writing this is almost a novelty @@StartBracket@@no high-level game@@EndBracket@@! Black has to go for the material, otherwise after White's  10.Ne2  , Black's 8...Qc7 loses meaning. }
9... cxd4 10. cxd4 { Now Black goes for the rook or is simply, clearly worse. }
10... Qc3+ 11. Qd2 Qxa1
{ 11...Qxd2+  12.Bxd2  is an excellent ending for White. } 12. Ne2
{ Black has won a rook but is about to lose his queen. White has three basic threats to win the black queen.
 a. 13. O-O, 14. Bb2, 15. Nc1 orb. 13. O-O, 14. Nc3, 15. Bb2 andc. 13. Nc3, 14. Bb1, 15. Bb2Black must be very precise to be only worse and not immediately lost! }
12... O-O 13. O-O
{ White has a large advantage.Beware!  13.Nc3?  is wrong due to  13...b5!  and Black's queen escapes;  14.O-O  b4  15.axb4  Ba6  16.b5  Qa5  17.bxa6  compared to our mainline Black is now some tempi up and can continue  17...Nxa6  with a better game. }
13... Be6 14. Bb2 Qxf1+ 15. Kxf1
{ Black has two rooks for the white queen, so one could make a mistake by thinking that things are not clear. Because of White's mobile pawn centre, matters are instead quite clear. White will push his e4-e5 pawn, take space and get a strong attack. }
*

