1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5
{ Black can also play  5...d5  , however after  6.cxd5  exd5  7.e3  c5  8.Bd3  O-O  9.Ne2  b6  it is only White who can choose between different possibilities. He can enter our mainline with  10.O-O  Ba6  11.f3  , or opt for a different pawn structure with  11.dxc5  bxc5  12.Bxa6  Nxa6  13.c4  or finally play  11.Bxa6  Nxa6  12.Qd3  Nc7  13.dxc5  bxc5  14.c4 }
6. f3 d5 7. cxd5 exd5 8. e3
{ Black here has a couple of sidelines, all leading to White's advantage, which I will point out. }
8... Bf5
{ A little played move that should not worry White, who continues by preparing the g4-push. }
9. Ne2 O-O { Or  9...Nc6  10.g4  leading to similar positions. } 10. g4 Nxg4
{ Here we find an old game of Tal, in which Black has sacrificed a piece, a sacrifice that does not work.If  10...Bg6  White has a promising position after  11.h4  or  11.Nf4  with h4 to follow.   11...h5  12.g5  Ne8  13.Nf4 }
11. fxg4 Qh4+ 12. Ng3
{ An improvement found by Stockfish; White gives up an exchange but gets perfect piece coordination.  12.Kd2  was also good enough as after  12...Be4  13.Rg1  cxd4  14.exd4  Black didn't have enough compensation for the piece and White easily won in Tal, M-Padevsky, N, Leipzig, 1960. }
12... Be4 13. Rg1 Qxh2 14. Nxe4
{ By sacrificing the rook White is able to develop the full attack potential of the bishop pair. The engine strongly prefers White after the text move. }
14... Qxg1 15. Nxc5 Qg3+ 16. Kd2
{ White has a large advantage. His pieces are well-coordinated and soon he will be the one having the attack. }
