[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch.8: 5...c5 6.f3 d5"]
[Black "6...d5 with 8.e3 c4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5
{ Black can also play  5...d5  , however after  6.cxd5  exd5  7.e3  c5  8.Bd3  O-O  9.Ne2  b6  it is only White who can choose between different possibilities. He can enter our mainline with  10.O-O  Ba6  11.f3  , or opt for a different pawn structure with  11.dxc5  bxc5  12.Bxa6  Nxa6  13.c4  or finally play  11.Bxa6  Nxa6  12.Qd3  Nc7  13.dxc5  bxc5  14.c4 }
6. f3 d5 7. cxd5 exd5 8. e3
{ Black here has a couple of sidelines, all leading to White's advantage, which I will point out. }
8... c4
{ This is another side line played by a number of players. Black's plan is obvious: to prevent Bd3, hindering White's natural development.The problem is that White is happy when the c3-d4 pawn chain is fixed and stable as it makes pushing the e4 pawn much easier. Black can easily get into big trouble here, White has to be precise in the order of moves though! }
9. g4
{ This is the precise order of moves for White! It is not easy to criticize the choices of players like Kasparov, Anand, Vidit, but I think they all chose the wrong order.All three of them went for  9.Ne2  which after  9...Nc6  10.g4  transposes, but Black has a much better move at his disposal:   9...h5!  White now has problems making a harmonious development or, to be more precise, he has problems conveniently executing his thematic push of the e4 pawn. The play is dynamic, Black is no worse.  10.g3  Nc6  11.Bg2  h4  12.O-O  hxg3  13.Nxg3  Be6  14.e4  Qd7  15.Bg5  White went on to win in Volkov, S - Alekseev, E, St. Petersburg, 2016. }
9... Nc6 10. Ne2
{ This position is very promising for White. White will roll his pawns and be ready to sacrifice his pawn on g4 in the process @@StartBracket@@Kasparov's idea!@@EndBracket@@ and get a strong attack. The devastating loss suffered by Kramnik at the hands of Vidit at the super-tournament in Wijk aan Zee speaks volumes about the dangers Black is facing here! }
10... h6 { Was Black's continuation in Kasparov Vs Polgar, Tilburg, 1997. } 11.
Bg2 Na5 { Aiming at b3. } 12. O-O Nb3 13. Ra2
{ The rook will be more comfortable on the second rank, from where it will be able to reach the kingside. }
13... O-O 14. Ng3 Bd7 15. Qe1 Re8
{ Now White gets his central pawns rolling, not caring about sacrificing the g4-pawn in the process. }
16. e4 dxe4 17. fxe4 Nxg4
{ Black's knight on b3 will remain out of play, so there was perhaps some logic in exchanging it for White's potential attacker  17...Nxc1  18.Qxc1  Nxg4  and White has a strong attack after  19.h3  Nf6  20.Raf2 }
18. Bf4 Qh4 19. h3 Nf6 20. e5
{ White has a strong pawn center, excellently coordinated pieces, and soon won in Kasparov, G @@StartBracket@@2820@@EndBracket@@-Polgar, J @@StartBracket@@2670@@EndBracket@@ Tilburg, 1997. }
*

