8... O-O 9. Bd3 b6 10. Ne2 Re8 { This most often transposes to our mainline. }
11. O-O Bb7
{ Keeping the light-squared bishops is not really played, and for good reason. The nature of the pawn structure simply implies that the presence of the light square bishop is advantageous to White, apart from the fact that it is an attacking piece once the e4 pawn push begins.White has various ways of playing this position, I will give an old game of White playing for the standard e4 pawn push getting an excellent position. }
12. Ng3
{ Black has to take d4 to get immediate pressure on White's centre in case he pushes the e4 pawn. }
12... Nc6
{ One of the advantages for White of having a light-squared bishop on the board can also be seen from the following line. }
13. Ra2 cxd4
{ Thanks to his light-squared bishop, White can take in the center with good attacking prospects. }
14. exd4
{ White's bishop on d3 is superior to its counterpart on b7.   White will have a promising attack: the knight will jump on f5, the rook will join the army on f2 or g2, in case White advances the g4-pawn. }
