1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5
{ Black can also play  5...d5  , however after  6.cxd5  exd5  7.e3  c5  8.Bd3  O-O  9.Ne2  b6  it is only White who can choose between different possibilities. He can enter our mainline with  10.O-O  Ba6  11.f3  , or opt for a different pawn structure with  11.dxc5  bxc5  12.Bxa6  Nxa6  13.c4  or finally play  11.Bxa6  Nxa6  12.Qd3  Nc7  13.dxc5  bxc5  14.c4 }
6. f3 d5 7. cxd5 exd5 8. e3
{ Black here has a couple of sidelines, all leading to White's advantage, which I will point out. }
8... O-O 9. Bd3 b6 10. Ne2 Ba6 11. O-O Bxd3
{ By exchanging the bishop Black tries to thwart White's plan, which revolves around the advance on e4. }
12. Qxd3 Re8 13. Ng3 Nc6
{ White has to play to push the e4 pawn and has two ways to prepare it:a. simple  14.Bb2  b.  14.Ra2  with Re2 and Bb2 to follow.Both moves were played by strong players. I think the straightforward  14.Bb2  is more dangerous for Black.While I haven't found a way for White's advantage, Black is walking a tightrope! }
14. Bb2
{ Black has tried many moves here and only one keeps the balance. The best for Black is to seek immediate counterplay by immediately hitting the white knight on g3, thus disturbing the thrust of the e4 pawn. }
14... Rc8
{ It's too slow, Black is thinking about the c-file while White will roll his pawns in the centre! White has an easy way to take advantage here, he simply prepares the e4 pawn advance. }
15. Rae1 { Black cannot stop 16.e4 and is already in trouble. } 15... Na5 16.
e4 { Black has a few jumps, but no real counterplay. } 16... Nc4 17. Bc1 cxd4
18. cxd4 dxe4 19. fxe4 Ne5 20. Qd2 Ng6 { White quickly gets a strong attack. }
21. e5 { My engine also likes  21.Bb2  followed by d5. } 21... Nd5 22. Nf5 Re6
23. Qf2 Qd7 24. h4
{ White has a free attack and soon won in Furman, S - Lilienthal, A, Moscow 1949/ URS-ch. }
