[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch.8: 5...c5 6.f3 d5"]
[Black "Navara's New Idea"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5
{ Black can also play  5...d5  , however after  6.cxd5  exd5  7.e3  c5  8.Bd3  O-O  9.Ne2  b6  it is only White who can choose between different possibilities. He can enter our mainline with  10.O-O  Ba6  11.f3  , or opt for a different pawn structure with  11.dxc5  bxc5  12.Bxa6  Nxa6  13.c4  or finally play  11.Bxa6  Nxa6  12.Qd3  Nc7  13.dxc5  bxc5  14.c4 }
6. f3 d5 7. cxd5 exd5 8. e3
{ Black here has a couple of sidelines, all leading to White's advantage, which I will point out. }
8... O-O 9. Bd3 b6 10. Ne2 Ba6 11. O-O Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Re8 13. Ng3 Nc6
{ White has to play to push the e4 pawn and has two ways to prepare it:a. simple  14.Bb2  b.  14.Ra2  with Re2 and Bb2 to follow.Both moves were played by strong players. I think the straightforward  14.Bb2  is more dangerous for Black.While I haven't found a way for White's advantage, Black is walking a tightrope! }
14. Bb2
{ Black has tried many moves here and only one keeps the balance. The best for Black is to seek immediate counterplay by immediately hitting the white knight on g3, thus disturbing the thrust of the e4 pawn. }
14... h5 { The main move for Black. } 15. e4 { Navara's almost new idea. }
15... h4
{ 15...c4!  Black's best reply.  16.Qe3  With his last move, Black has disturbed White's co-ordination and the game is now balanced. The engine will give a number of zero-zero lines, many of which are difficult for a human to understand. I will give a probable human-game-line that also objectively leads to equality.  16...dxe4  17.fxe4  Now Black goes for his usual counterplay.    17...h4!  18.Nf5  Nxe4  19.Qf3  Qf6  White needs to improve his bishop.  20.Rad1  Ng5!  21.Qh5  Qg6!  22.Qxh4   For a reader willing to investigate further, I advise to delve in  22.Qxg6!?  fxg6  23.Nxh4  Re2  24.Nxg6!  Rxb2  25.d5  White is a piece down but, according to Stockfish, has full compensation. The evaluation is zero.  22...Re2  23...Nf3+ is a threat.  23.Qg4  Rxb2  And everything ends peacefully.  24.Nh4  Qh6  25.Nf5  Qg6= }
16. Nf5 g6
{ 16...dxe4  If Black decides to grab a pawn, White gets the advantage but must be precise.  17.fxe4  Rxe4  18.Nxg7!  Ne5!  Black's best practical defence that requires precision from White.  19.Qh3  cxd4   19...Nc4  loses to  20.Bc1  Kxg7  21.Bg5  20.cxd4  Nc4  21.Nf5!  Nxb2  22.Qb3  It seems that White recovers his piece and because of the weak black king has a clear advantage. Well, Black can still demand accuracy from White!  22...Nh5!   If  22...Nd5  White is better after  23.Rac1  The Black's Nb2 is trapped and the black queen cannot move.  23.Qf3!  Nf6  White must now calmly bring another piece into the attack.  24.Rac1!  Threat is 25.Rc6  24...Qd5   If  24...Re6  White plays  25.Qh3!  @@StartBracket@@Threat is 26.Qxh4 @@EndBracket@@  25...Re4  26.Qb3  White will grab Black's knight on b2 in favourable circumstances.  25.Rc6!  White can still penetrate with his rook!  25...Re6  26.Qf4!  And to prevent mate Black will lose decisive material.  26...Qxc6  27.Qh6!  Ne8  28.Ne7+  Rxe7  29.Qxc6  Rd8  30.Qb5+-  White wins the black Nb2 and should win. }
17. Nxh4 dxe4 18. fxe4 Nxe4 19. Rf4
{ Ne4 cannot move because of Nxg6, Black does not have a good reply. } 19...
Qe7 20. Nxg6 Qg5 21. Rxe4 Rxe4 22. Qxe4 Qxg6 23. Qe2
{ White was a solid pawn up and easily took home the point in Navara,D @@StartBracket@@2735@@EndBracket@@ -Sturua,Z @@StartBracket@@2548@@EndBracket@@ Gjakova 2016. }
