[Black "8.dxc5 Qa5 9.e4 Nc7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5 6. f3 d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5
{ This move is, in modern practice, played more often than  7...exd5  . White has here a mainline  8.dxc5  , which is the one I recommend, and two sidelines,  8.Qd2  and  8.Qd3  . }
8. dxc5 Qa5 9. e4
{ White is temporarily a pawn up, but has a damaged structure and is likely to lose his extra pawn. White often does not mind losing a pawn and even sacrifices one @@StartBracket@@or two@@EndBracket@@ to gain the initiative.If Black develops ...Na6, White reacts mostly with Bxa6; the positions with opposite colour bishops, with an extra pawn, are often better for White.Of Black's three possible knight retreats,  9...Nf6  and  9...Ne7  have become the main lines and  9...Nc7  the sideline. }
9... Nc7
{ The knight's third jump is not fashionable and in the practice of the Grandmasters it is rarely seen today. The reason is that we get an ending with, normally, only two possible outcomes. While it is certainly far from easy to squeeze the entire point as White, it is certainly no fun to be Black. }
10. Qd4
{ After  10.Be3  O-O  11.Kf2  Nca6!  Black wants to grab White's c5 pawn while making sure he has ...Rd8. @@StartBracket@@  11...Nba6?  isn't good for Black, as after  12.Qd6  Black doesn't have ...Rd8. The white queen is quite annoying on d6. This position has been reached in Mamedyarov, S - Vidit, S Kolkata 2018.@@EndBracket@@  12.a4!  Nxc5  13.Qd6  we have, strangely enough, transposed to 9...Nf6 line }
10... f6 { By far the main move otherwise, White is just easily better. } 11.
Qb4 Nc6 12. Qxa5 Nxa5
{ This is the position White can get after Black's retreat with 9...Nc7. As I've already said, while it's far from easy to squeeze the entire point as White, it's not much fun being Black.Pay attention to White's ideas of sacrificing the knight on d4 @@StartBracket@@once Black advances ...e5@@EndBracket@@, it is a typical sacrifice in those positions. Black should hold with precise play, but it is White who is pressing. }
13. Rb1
{ Improving the rook and running away from ...Nb3 threat. Black has two main moves  13...Bd7  @@StartBracket@@by far the main move, played in a majority of games@@EndBracket@@ and  13...e5  . }
13... e5
{ Looks logical, to build a pawn chain, it gets close to equality, but it does not equalize. White should be slightly better. }
14. f4
{ Opening up the position for his bishops, and Black has to take. If Black does not take, White will, and play Nf3 hitting the pawn on e5. }
14... exf4 15. Bxf4 Ne6 16. Bd6
{ White's pawn structure may look damaged, but it is difficult for Black to capture any of the pawns for free. With 17. e5 to follow, opening up the position for White's bishop pair, White has some advantage. }
