[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Ch.9: 5...c5 with 9...Nf6 and 9...Ne7"]
[Black "8.dxc5 Qa5 9.e4 Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5 6. f3 d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5
{ This move is, in modern practice, played more often than  7...exd5  .  White has here a mainline  8.dxc5  , which is the one I recommend, and two sidelines,  8.Qd2  and  8.Qd3  . }
8. dxc5 Qa5 9. e4
{ White is temporarily a pawn up, but has a damaged structure and is likely to lose his extra pawn. White often does not mind losing a pawn and even sacrifices one @@StartBracket@@or two@@EndBracket@@ to gain the initiative.If Black develops ...Na6, White reacts mostly with Bxa6; the positions with opposite colour bishops, with an extra pawn, are often better for White.Of Black's three possible knight retreats,  9...Nf6  and  9...Ne7  have become the mainlines and  9...Nc7  the sideline. }
9... Nf6 10. Be3 O-O
{ By far the most played move of White here is  11.Qb3  , but I would like to propose the new and little played @@StartBracket@@three games in the database at the time of writing@@EndBracket@@  11.a4!? }
11. Kf2
{ Another interesting option for White, which is also a good move order to test Black's preparation as the best continuation for Black is  11...Nfd7  , after which White has an option to play  12.a4  transposing into our mainline.  12.Ne2  is an alternative, play might continue with  12...Nxc5  13.Nd4  Black has regained his pawn. White has improved his development and is ready to sacrifice material to further develop his initiative.  The position is probably equal, but Black must be precise!  13...Bd7  14.a4!  White takes space by challenging Black to take one of the white pawns. If Black refuses to take it, White will be better.  We can follow a high-level game.  14...Qc7  15.a5!  Rd8  16.Qb1  e5  White correctly goes for 2 bishops Vs 2 knights position  17.Nb5  Bxb5  18.Bxb5  Black has no counterplay and will have problems protecting his queenside. White went on to win in Navara, D - So, W, Saint Louis, 2019. }
11... Na6 { White goes for his 'standard reaction'. } 12. Bxa6 Qxa6 13. Qd6
{ Balck has some problems here, he is a pawn down, although White has doubled pawns on the c-file, it is still an extra pawn, and the White king is safe. White has a better position. }
13... Qa5 14. Ne2 Rd8 15. Qg3 { White can get some attacking chances. } 15...
Bd7 16. Bd4
{ This is the kind of position White actually loves, we have this opposite-colored bishop position where White has an extra pawn and a better-placed bishop, there are some threats on the kingside. }
16... Ne8 17. h4
{ All of a sudden, it is very handy for the White king to be on f2. White will continue pushing and has good attacking prospects. }
