[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5 6. f3 d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8.
dxc5 Qa5 9. e4 Ne7 10. Be3 O-O 11. Qb3
{ Definitely White's main and probably best move. } 11... Nd7
{ This move has the disadvantage of allowing White to execute a favorable trade. }
12. Bb5 Qc7 13. Bxd7 Bxd7 14. Ne2
{ These opposite color bishops positions are simply better for White, who is also a sound pawn up, and Black has no compensation for it. }
14... e5
{ A sound move, in view of the pawn structure, but now White gets the d5-square outpost. }
15. c4 Nc6 16. Nc3
{ Probably the best move for White, forcing the transition into a pawn-up rook endgame.The high-level practical test went  16.Rd1  Be6  17.Rd5  looks fancy, but Black doesn't need to take.  17...Na5  18.Qc3  Now Black creates counterplay.  18...b6!  19.Rxe5  Nxc4  20.Rg5  f6  21.Nd4  Black can hold.  21...Qf7!  @@StartBracket@@The aforementioned game went  21...Bf7?  22.Nf5+  and White soon won in Vidit, S - Andreikin, D Moscow 2019.@@EndBracket@@@@StartFEN@@r4rk1/p4qpp/1p2bp2/2P3R1/2nNP3/P1Q1BP2/6PP/4K2R w K - 2 22@@EndFEN@@  22.Nxe6  Qxe6  23.Rd5  Nxe3  24.Qxe3  White needs time to castle, and Black can use it to save the game.  24...Rad8!  25.Rxd8  Rxd8  26.O-O  Qa2!  and Black can easily draw. }
16... Nd4 17. Bxd4 exd4 18. Nd5 Qxc5 { Now White needs some good calculation. }
19. Qxb7 { White is about to castle, so Black's next move is forced. } 19... d3
20. Qxd7 Rad8 21. Qe7
{ And White gets a pawn-up rook ending.  21...d2+  22.Kd1  Rxd5  23.Qxc5  is the same.   21...Qd4  22.Kd2  looks winning for White. }
21... Rxd5 22. Qxc5 d2+
{ 22...Rxc5  only improves White's position after  23.Rc1  with Kd2 to follow. }
23. Ke2 Rxc5 24. Kxd2 Rxc4 25. Rhc1
{ Is White closer to victory or Black closer to a draw? I would judge White to be closer to victory. }
