1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5 6. f3 d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8.
dxc5 Qa5 9. e4 Ne7 10. Be3 O-O 11. Qb3
{ Definitely White's main and probably best move. } 11... Qc7
{ Black's most played @@StartBracket@@and also probably the best@@EndBracket@@ answer. Black wants 12...Nd7 followed by ...Nxc5. }
12. Bb5
{ White stops Black's  12...Nd7  @@StartBracket@@threat is  13.Bxd7  @@EndBracket@@. }
12... Nec6 13. Ne2 Na5 14. Qb4
{ We have many games here and Black struggles. White will make his strategic exchange, namely his Bb5 for Nb8. Black struggles to get back his pawn.Normally this position seems to me to be open to two outcomes. Black needs to push ...e5 to activate his bishop. }
14... e5 15. O-O Be6
{ It was Anand's famous game and a perfect example of a typical pawn structure improvement with a piece sacrifice. }
16. Nd4 exd4 17. cxd4 Nbc6 18. Qc3 Ne7
{ White has two strong central pawns plus an excellent pair of bishops for his sacrificed piece. Black would like to return his piece, but White is not interested in taking it! }
19. Rfd1 Rad8 20. Bf2 { Improving the bishop. } 20... a6 21. Bg3 Qc8 22. Bf1
{ White was clearly better and went on to win in Anand, V @@StartBracket@@2810@@EndBracket@@-Wang, H @@StartBracket@@2731@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2011. }
*

