[Black " Game 1: Gheorghiu, Florin vs. Fischer, Robert James,Olympiad-17 Final A ,Havana,1966"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 d5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 O-O 7. cxd5 exd5 8.
e3 { Fischer comes up with a strange opening experiment. } 8... Nh5
{ I have not analysed this move in the theoretical part because it has no theoretical value. I'm pretty sure that the only reason Fischer chose this knight jump was to take the game out of theory and confuse things.In reality Black only confuses himself, because he loses time with his knight jumps and White gets a nice space advantage. }
9. Qc2 Re8
{ White reacts well and, in the spirit of the Saemisch variation, takes up space! }
10. g4 Nf4 11. h4 c5 12. Kf2
{ The white king is safe on f2-square, black must continue to waste time in his knight jumps. }
12... Ng6 { The first critical moment. White plays a regular developing move. }
13. Bd3
{ My Stockfish 14 indicates that White is gaining a big advantage with the straight  13.h5!  Nf8  14.h6  Black's king position will be weak.  14...g6  Now White opens the a1-h8 diagonal.  15.dxc5!  @@StartBracket@@White wants Bb2 with c4 to follow@@EndBracket@@  15...Nc6  16.Bb2  Qe7  17.Qd2  White will get an attack, the best for black is to get a pawn, at least winning some material.  17...Ne5   17...Nd7  18.c4  looks excellent for White.  18.c4!  dxc4  19.Rc1  Qxc5  Now best for White is to send black queen all the way to h8.  20.Bxe5  Qxe5  21.f4!  the black queen must retreat.  21...Qh8   21...Qe7  loses for Black after  22.Bxc4  The black king is weak, White combines threats. Here are some sample lines:  22...Be6   22...Bxg4  loses to  23.Qb2  as after the forced  23...Ne6  24.Bxe6  fxe6  25.Kg3+-  the black bishop is misplaced, the black king weak and White has a winning advantage.  25...Bf5  26.Qe5  Rac8  27.Nf3  White has a nice domination, the threat is 28.e4   The immediate  27.Rxc8  Rxc8  28.e4  should win as well.  27...Bc2  28.Rh2  Ba4  29.Rxc8  Rxc8  30.Rd2  with Ng5 @@StartBracket@@also followed by Ne4, which is on the cards@@EndBracket@@ and Rd6 to come. To evaluate with computer language the position is more than +4!  23.Qb2  f6  24.Nf3  The material is equal, but the black king is decisively weak.  24...Rac8  Now White needs to be a bit precise.  25.Bb5!  Bd7   25...Red8  26.g5+-  is, for example, +5 evaluation.  26.Bxd7!  Qxe3+  27.Kg3  Nxd7  28.Rhe1  and Black cannot keep 'his stuff together'.  28...Qb6  29.Qd2  29...Qd8   Or  29...Qb5  30.Qa2+  Kf8  31.Rxc8  Rxc8  32.Qe6+-  30.Qd5+  Kf8  31.Rxe8+  Qxe8  32.Qd6+  Kf7  Now White forces Black under a deadly pin.  33.Re1  Qd8  34.Rd1  Rc7  now is the time to open the black king position further.  35.g5+-  22.g5!  Be6  The fact that Black is for the time being a pawn up, does not matter.  23.Nf3  At first glance the position perhaps, at least to the human eye, does not seem so clear. Black cannot coordinate his pieces and White has a clear advantage.  23...b5   Or  23...Rad8  24.Qb4±  24.Bg2  Rad8  25.Qb4  25...a6   25...Rd3  Loses to  26.Ne5  Rb3  27.Qd6+-  Look at the black queen locked up on the h8-square!  26.Rhd1  Black's position will soon collapse. }
13... Nc6 14. Ne2 Be6
{ White obviously should advance his pawns, but how?   As usual in similar positions closing the center makes White's job, which is to push e4 and roll his pawns, easier;  14...c4  15.Bf5  Na5   15...Bxf5  loses to  16.gxf5!  Nf8  17.e4+-  16.Ng3  Nb3  17.Rb1  b5  now White simply rolls his pawns.  18.e4 }
15. g5
{ Better was  15.h5!  Nf8  16.h6  g6  17.Nf4  White cannot push his central pawns immediately, but does have a nice space advantage, while Black's counterplay is limited.  17...Rc8  18.Qb2  Qf6  19.Kg3± }
15... Rc8 16. h5 Nf8 { Now Black has counterplay and the game is unclear. } 17.
g6
{ Fischer likely reacts the best.   17.h6  g6  isn't the same as @@StartFEN@@r2qr1k1/pp3ppp/2n1b1n1/2pp4/3P2PP/P1PBPP2/2Q1NK2/R1B4R w - - 6 15@@EndFEN@@  15.h5!  Nf8  16.h6  , as white pawn on g5 hangs, while Black threathens @@StartFEN@@2rqrnk1/pp3p1p/2n1b1pP/2pp2P1/3P4/P1PBPP2/2Q1NK2/R1B4R b - - 0 18@@EndFEN@@  18...c4  winning a piece. }
17... fxg6 18. hxg6 h6 19. Qb1
{ Black Nc6 has to move to a better square, but where? } 19... Na5
{ Probably better was  19...Ne7!  as after  20.Nf4  the d5-square is covered, so Black can retreat.  20...Bd7  White has to go for e4-pawn push, doing it right now does not seem to work out well.  21.e4  The position is sharp. Play may continue   In the case of a pawn grab  21.Qxb7  Black has good compensation after  21...Ne6=∞  21...cxd4  22.cxd4  Nfxg6!  23.Nxg6  Nxg6  Now problably Black's best is  24.e5  Nh4!  and after   Your engine will suggest a piece sacrifice  24...Rf8  to lead to equality after  25.Bxg6  Bg4  26.f4  Rxc1!  27.Qxc1  Qg5  White has just one move to stay in the game.  28.Bf5!  The position looks promising for Black but my engine gives multiple zeros.   28.Kg3  Qxg6-+  28...Rxf5   28...Qxf5  29.Qe3=  29.Kg3  Qg6  30.Rh4=  25.Bxh6!  Re6!  if anyone is better here, it is not White. }
20. Nf4 { White is better now. } 20... c4 21. Bc2 Rc6
{ White improves his rook in the 'Standard Saemisch Way'. } 22. Ra2
{ The position is very complicated to play for a human, even if your name is Fischer! }
22... Nd7
{ Silicon brain gives as best  22...Bc8!  @@StartBracket@@possibly leading to an exchange sacrifice after 23.Ba4@@EndBracket@@ and comes up with a whole bunch of crazy variations! }
23. a4 { A clever move, improving the Bc1. } 23... Nf6 24. Ba3 Qd7 25. Rb2 b6
{ Now White is ready for the central pawn push, but delays it in order to do it under the best circumstances. }
26. Rb5
{ This gives Fischer a chance to escape!   The immediate  26.e4+-  was winning because Black cannot prevent material losses, e.g.  26...dxe4  27.Bxe4  Nxe4+  28.Qxe4  and White wins a piece @@StartBracket@@Black will lose his Be6@@EndBracket@@.  28...Rcc8  29.Rh5!  Bg4   29...Nc6  30.d5+-  30.Re5+- }
26... Nb7
{ This loses, as the e4-pawn push now decides.   26...Nb3!  was leading to crazy complications, likely saving the game!  27.e4  Now Black needs to find  27...Bg4!  White also needs to be precise   27...dxe4?  loses to  28.Bxe4  and again black Be6 will be lost after  28...Nxe4+  29.Qxe4+-  28.e5!   28.fxg4?  loses to  28...Qxg4  and Black has a winning attack after  29.Ng2  Nxe4+  30.Bxe4  Rxe4-+  28...Bxf3!  now we see the biggest difference compared to 26...Nb7? Bishop cannot be taken due to 29...Nd2+ fork.   The engine also gives  28...Nd2  29.Qc1  Bxf3  30.Rh4  Nb3!  and some crazy lines leading to equality.  29.Bf5  Qd8  30.exf6  Rxf6  and this mess ends in a perpetual check.  31.Re1  Rxe1  32.Qxe1  Be4!  33.Bxe4  Rxf4+  34.Bf3  Black now forces a draw by perpetual check.  34...Qh4+  35.Ke2  Re4+!  36.Bxe4  Qxe4+  37.Kf1  Qh1+  38.Kf2  Qh4+= }
27. e4 { White will soon get a decisive material advantage. } 27... dxe4
{ 27...Bg4  now loses to  28.e5+-  as after  28...Bxf3  29.Bf5  Qd8  30.Kxf3  there is no ...Nd2+. }
28. Bxe4 Rcc8 29. Re5 { Black cannot prevent material losses. } 29... Bg4
{ Or  29...Nd6  30.Bxd6  Qxd6  31.Nxe6  Nd7   Or  31...Rxe6  32.Rxe6  Qxe6  33.Bf5+-  32.Rf5  Rxe6  33.Bd5+- }
30. Nd5 Rxe5 31. Nxf6+ gxf6 32. dxe5
{ White has many ways to win this position, with @@StartFEN@@2r3k1/pn1q4/1p3pPp/4P3/P1p1B1b1/B1P2P2/5K2/1Q5R w - - 0 32@@EndFEN@@  33.exf6  and @@StartFEN@@2r3k1/pn1q4/1p3pPp/4P3/P1p1B1b1/B1P2P2/5K2/1Q5R w - - 0 32@@EndFEN@@  33.fxg4  being the main threats. }
32... Nc5 33. Bxc5 Qd2+ 34. Kg3 Bxf3 35. Bxf3 Rxc5
{ White takes the most practical approach getting into a won endgame. } 36. Qc1
Qxc1 37. Rxc1 Rxe5 38. Kf4
{ This ending is easily won for White. The rest of the game does not need any comments. }
38... Kg7 39. Be4 h5 40. Rd1 Re7 41. Rd5 Kh6 42. Rd6 Kg7 43. Rc6 h4 44. Rxc4 h3
