[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black " Game 2: Kasparov, Garry vs. Polgar, Judit, Tilburg,1997."]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 d5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8.
dxc5 Qa5 9. e4 Ne7 10. Be3 O-O 11. Qb3 Qc7 12. Bb5 Nec6 13. Ne2 Na5 14. Qb4 e5
15. O-O Be6
{ Anand now comes up with a well-known idea of piece sacrifice, but never seen before in this particular position, and therefore a novelty.   Due to this game, and the piece sacrifice idea, Black's main line, as given in the theory part of the course, became  15...Na6 }
16. Nd4 { This positional piece sacrifice close 15...Be6 line. } 16... exd4 17.
cxd4
{ As a result of the sacrifice, White has corrected his pawn structure. White has only two pawns for his sacrificed piece, but look at the impressive central pawn chain! Black would like to return his piece to destroy it, but White is willing to accept it on his terms.Black's problem is that White controls a lot of space, making it difficult to create counterplay. }
17... Nbc6
{ Anand's victory was so impressive and the sacrifice so objectively strong that we had very few players willing to side with Black. One of these players was my namesake Andei Sokolov, a former Soviet GM who has been living in France for over twenty years. In that game, too, Black was in trouble. The position is simply better for White.   The game went  17...Nac6  18.Qc3  Ne7  19.Bf2  White follows up on Anand's idea.   Probably more precise was  19.Rad1!  The threat is 20.d5  19...Rd8  20.Bf2!  Nbc6   20...b6?  hoping to return the piece and save the game after  21.d5  Nxd5   21...Bxd5?  does not help either  22.exd5  Nxd5  23.Qc4+-  and Black loses at least a piece.  22.exd5  Bxd5  does not work due to  23.Bh4!  and Black loses material;  23...f6  24.Rxd5  Rxd5  25.Bc4  Black now loses a full rook.  25...Qxc5+  26.Bf2  Qd6  27.Qb3+-  21.Bg3  Black can enter the endgame with  21...Qa5   21...Qd7  22.d5  is bad for Black. White gets his piece back.  22.Qxa5  Nxa5  but the endgame is lost for Black after the simple  23.Bc7  Bc4  In the case of   23...Nb3  24.Bxd8  Rxd8  25.d5  Bc8  White simply rolls his pawns:  26.c6  bxc6  27.dxc6+-  24.Bxa5  Bxb5  25.Bxd8  Rxd8  26.Rf2+-  stopping white pawns will cost Black a piece.   It is good to mention that precision is always needed! If White places the other rook to the d1-square  19.Rfd1  and follows up with  19...Rd8  20.Bf2  Nbc6  21.Bg3  Black saves the game after  21...Qa5!  22.Qxa5  Nxa5  23.Bc7  Nb3!  24.Bxd8  Rxd8=  and a draw is the most likely result.  19...Nbc6  20.Bg3  Qd7   20...Qa5  leads to hopeless position for Black after  21.Qxa5  Nxa5  22.Bd6+-  21.Bd6  White was clearly better. Black managed to return his piece for White's two central pawns and eventually saved the game in Cossin,S @@StartBracket@@2498@@EndBracket@@-Sokolov,A @@StartBracket@@2532@@EndBracket@@ Brest 2018.   17...b6?  The hope of making some exchange leads to a hopeless position for Black after the simple  18.d5+- }
18. Qc3 Ne7
{ How dire the situation is for Black is perhaps best illustrated by my number one suggestion of Stockfish! Its first line is  18...Nb3!?  19.Rab1  Nbxd4  gives a knight for only one pawn @@StartBracket@@!!@@EndBracket@@ in order to break White's pawn chain. Naturally, a human player does not choose for such moves, as after  20.Bxd4  Nxd4  21.Qxd4  Rac8  22.Rbc1±  White is simply a sound pawn up. }
19. Rfd1 Rad8 20. Bf2 a6
{ In the case of  20...b6  Black remains completely tied up after  21.Bg3!   A dream scenario for Black would be something like  21.c6  Nexc6!  22.d5  Bd7  23.dxc6   In the case of  23.Rac1  Black is likely to survive after  23...Qe5!  24.dxc6  Qxb5  25.cxd7  Rxd7⩲  Bxc6±  White is still clearly better thanks to the bishop pair and pawn majority, but Black might survive.  Qb7  22.Rab1+- }
21. Bg3 Qc8 22. Bf1 b6 { 22...Nac6  23.Bd6  with d5 to follow. } 23. Rab1
{ The most precise, because Black cannot move - and also cannot prevent losing material. }
23... Nb3 24. Rxb3 Bxb3 25. Qxb3 bxc5 26. d5
{ The material on the board has changed a bit, but Black's situation is as terrible as ever. White still has a powerful central pawn chain and a strong bishop pair. Black is passive and cannot make use of his extra exchange. Black hopes to break White's chain of central pawns thus opening files for his rooks. }
26... Ng6 27. Qb6 f5
{ This active-looking move changes nothing. White collects two pawns and becomes the one with the material advantage. }
28. Bxa6 Qd7 29. Bb5 Qf7 30. exf5 Qxf5 31. Qxc5
{ White now has material advantage, while still having the full control of the position. One of white passed pawns @@StartBracket@@'a' or 'd'@@EndBracket@@ is either going to queen or cost Black decisive material to stop it. }
31... Rc8 32. Qd4 Rfd8 33. a4
{ White will calmly push his passed pawns sailing to an easy victory. Black's position is absolutely hopeless and resignation is not premature. }
*

