[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Game 3: Botvinnik, Mikhail Moisevich vs. Keres, Paul, The Hague/Moscow,1948"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 Bb4 4. e3 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Nf6 7. cxd5 exd5 8.
f3 c4 9. Ne2
{ As mentioned in the 'theory part', I prefer for White to go  9.g4!  Nc6  10.Ne2  move order. }
9... Nc6
{ As mentioned in the 'theory part' Black can try to take advantage of this move order by playing  9...h5! }
10. g4 h6 11. Bg2
{ Black goes for a plan to bring her knight to the b3-square @@StartBracket@@plan relatively often seen in similar positions@@EndBracket@@ }
11... Na5 12. O-O Nb3 13. Ra2
{ This rook lift is typical for Saemisch positions. White will at some stage open the center and the rook will swing to the kingside. }
13... O-O 14. Ng3 Bd7 15. Qe1
{ White is getting ready to push e4 and sacrifice a pawn on g4 @@StartBracket@@so Kasparov removes his queen for a possible ...Bxg4 tempi@@EndBracket@@.   It is good to observe that immediate  15.e4!?  was definitely possible as White has more than 'just a compensation' after  15...dxe4  16.fxe4  Bxg4  17.Qe1→ }
15... Re8
{ Now Kasparov feels 'the time is right' for the central pawn push @@StartBracket@@which results in a pawn sacrifice@@EndBracket@@. }
16. e4 dxe4 17. fxe4
{ Black is already deep in trouble and is also facing an unpleasant dilemma! If Black @@StartBracket@@the way the game went@@EndBracket@@ does not now take ...Nxc1 @@StartBracket@@the last moment for Black to be able to do so!@@EndBracket@@, White will move his bishop to f4 and Black's knight on b3 might remain stuck there until the end of the game @@StartBracket@@the way it indeed happened!@@EndBracket@@. }
17... Nxg4
{ However, if Black takes  17...Nxc1  and now after  18.Qxc1  Nxg4  Black still has bad positions after  19.h3  Nf6  20.Raf2  the problem for Black here is that logical moves do the job for White  20...Nh7  21.e5   21.Rxf7?!  gives Black counterplay  21...Ng5⇆  21...Rf8   Or  21...Ng5  22.Kh2  and White easily builds on a winning attack on the kingside.  22.Ne4  22...Ng5  23.Nf6+!  the most precise for White   23.Nxg5  Qxg5  24.Qxg5  hxg5  25.Bxb7±  23...gxf6   23...Kh8?  loses to prosaic  24.h4  gxf6  25.hxg5+-  24.Rxf6  White has many ways to win this position  24...Nh7   Or  24...Re8  25.Rxh6  and White wins in a few moves, possible line can go  25...Re6  Or   25...Nh7  26.Rff6  26.Rff6  Nh7  27.Be4!  Nxf6  28.Qg5+  Kf8  29.exf6  25.Qxh6  Kh8  26.Rxf7 }
18. Bf4 { Now the knight on b3 stays there until the end of the game. } 18...
Qh4 19. h3 Nf6 20. e5 Rad8
{ 20...Bxh3  loses to  21.Bxh3  Qxh3  22.Rh2  White has winning attack here working in a number of ways. I will give one possible line  22...Qe6   22...Qg4  23.Rg2+-   Or  22...Qd7  23.Bxh6  Ng4  24.Nf5  Nxh2  25.Qg3  g6  26.Kxh2  23.Bxh6  Ng4  24.Bxg7  Nxh2  25.Kxh2  Kxg7  26.Nf5+  to prevent mate Black loses her queen and then still gets mated. }
21. Qf2 Nh5 22. Bxh6 { White got his pawn back, while the attack continues. }
22... Re7
{ Judit defends best under circumstances.   22...gxh6?  loses immediately to  23.Qxf7+  Kh8  24.Nxh5   22...Qxg3  loses to  23.Qxf7+  Kh7  24.Qxh5  gxh6  25.Rf6+-   22...Nxg3??  runs into mate in two  23.Qxf7+  Kh8  24.Qxg7 }
23. Nf5
{ Exclamation mark is for the practicality. Endgame is easily won for White.  Your computer engine will give as strongest   23.Nxh5  Qxh5  24.Bxg7  Kxg7  25.Qf6+  Kf8  26.Bd5  but why bother calculating this... }
23... Qxf2+ 24. Rfxf2
{ 24.Raxf2?  runs into fork and gives Black survival chances after  24...Bxf5  25.Rxf5  Ng3± }
24... Re6
{ 24...Bxf5  25.Rxf5  Re6  leads to a hopeless ending for Black  26.Rxh5  Rxh6  27.Rxh6  gxh6  28.Bxb7+- }
25. Be3 Bc6 26. Bf1
{ Last precise move. 27.Be2 is a terrible threat, so Black loses c4-pawn. }
26... f6 { 26...Bd5  indeed loses to  27.Be2  g6  28.Nh6+ } 27. Bxc4 Bd5 28.
Be2 { Black cannot prevent losing more material. } 28... fxe5
{ In the case of  28...g6  White has many good options...easy win being  29.c4  Be4   29...Bc6  30.d5+-  30.Nd6+- }
29. Bxh5 { White is a piece up, while the attack actually still continues }
29... exd4 30. Bg5 Rd7 31. Rae2 Be4 32. Nxd4 *

