1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 Ne4
{ This rare line is nowadays @@StartBracket@@almost@@EndBracket@@ not played at all and therefore I did not include it in the 'theory part'. White gets an advantage by logical developing moves @@StartBracket@@not needing to do anything special@@EndBracket@@. There are two main ideas behind the  5...Ne4  move.Black's first idea is purely psychological - to get the White player 'out of the book' and force him/her to play @@StartBracket@@relatively@@EndBracket@@ unexplored positions from an early stage of the game. Black's 'chess technical' idea behind the  5...Ne4  move is @@StartBracket@@in a way@@EndBracket@@ similar to  5...O-O  6.f3  Nh5  7.Nh3  f5  line, Black wants to slow down White's e4-pawn push. However, it is unclear how much Black really 'slows White down', as Black's knight will have to retreat from the e4-square. I had this game about 18 years ago vs Michael Adams where he wanted to surprise me with this rare line. Given that Black does not have a threat to take ...Nxc3, I decided to develop calmly. }
6. e3
{ Another road to White's advantage is the more aggressive  6.Qc2  aiming for a quick e4-pawn push @@StartBracket@@basically willing to kill Black's idea of 'slowing White down' - White wants Nh3, f3 followed by e4@@EndBracket@@  6...f5  7.Nh3  d6  now White goes for his central pawn push  8.f3  Nf6  9.e4  fxe4  we are following the game from Botvinnik-Tal match, now White's play can be improved on with  10.Ng5!  and Black is in trouble!   The actual game went  10.fxe4  now Black stabilized the center with  10...e5  @@StartBracket@@the reason behind Black's 7... d6 move@@EndBracket@@  11.Nf2  O-O  game was balanced and ended in a draw in Botvinnik, M-Tal,M Moscow 1960  10...exf3     If Black refuses to accept White's pawn sacrifice and plays  10...e5  White is better after  11.Nxe4  as Black cannot go for quick development with  11...Nxe4  12.Qxe4  O-O  @@StartBracket@@aiming for ...Bf5@@EndBracket@@ as White has  13.Bd3  Bf5  14.Qd5+!  Kh8  15.Bxf5  Rxf5  16.Qxb7  Nd7  17.O-O  and Black does not have compensation for his pawn deficit.  11.Bd3  White has development advantage and attacking prospects worth @@StartBracket@@much@@EndBracket@@ more than a pawn. Actually here Black can lose very quickly, e.g.  11...Qe7   11...fxg2  12.Qxg2  O-O  13.O-O  now hoping to quickly develop Nb8  13...Nc6  leads to a disaster for Black after  14.Ne4!  Nxe4  15.Bh6!  Qe7  16.Bxe4  at first glance, this position may look like 'well...White has some attack'....in reality Black is completely tied up @@StartBracket@@simply cannot develop@@EndBracket@@, in 'Stockfish language' this position is +5 !!  16...Bd7  17.Bg5!  Qe8  18.Rxf8+  Qxf8  19.Rf1  Qe8  20.Qh3  g6   20...h6?  loses immediately to  21.Bxh6  21.Qh4+-  Black cannot create any counterplay, is sitting duck waiting for the execution!  12.O-O  fxg2  13.Qxg2  O-O  and now comes the standard 'Saemisch rook lift'  14.Ra2!  White is attacking with all his pieces, Black being in a serious trouble. To use 'Stockfish language' White @@StartBracket@@while being two pawns down@@EndBracket@@ is on more than +1 ! }
6... O-O
{ 6...d5?!  creating ...Nxc3 threat is bad for Black as he will simply get a  bad version of ...d5 type lines  7.Qc2  c5  8.Bd3  now black knight will have to retreat and Black will simply get a bad version of known positions  8...cxd4  9.exd4  Qa5  10.Ne2  now knight has to retreat  10...Nf6  11.cxd5  Qxd5   In the case Black takes  11...exd5  not entering 'hanging pawns in the center' type positions, White can quickly develop a kingside attack  12.f3  O-O  13.g4!  12.O-O  O-O  13.c4  Qc6  14.Bb2±  Black has lost oceans of time, White is much better in this 'hanging pawns in the center'type position and easily won in Berkes,F  @@StartBracket@@2676@@EndBracket@@-Palac,M @@StartBracket@@2543@@EndBracket@@ Schwarzach 2018   If Black wants to be inventive with  6...f5  7.Bd3  Qg5?!  Black ends only confusing himself   In the case of  7...Nxc3  White has various ways to be better, the most aggressive being  8.Qh5+   White can also choose for  8.Qc2  Ne4  9.Bxe4  fxe4  10.Qxe4  O-O  11.Ne2  White has advantage here.  8...g6  9.Qh6  Black is behind in development, having weaknesses  9...Qf6  10.f3  Black's knight on c3 is almost trapped  10...c5  11.h4!  cxd4  12.h5  position is sharp, however tactics strongly favour White! To a human-'White has a strong attack'. To a computer, it is +2!   7...O-O  transposes to the game.  8.g3  Nxc3  9.Qc2  Ne4  10.f3  Nf6  11.Ne2  White starts rolling his pawns and soon gets crushing attack. It is useful to observe that absence of c3 pawn in many lines works to White's favour as a1-h8 diagonal is now open. }
7. Bd3 f5 8. Ne2
{ Black will have to retreat his knight and he does not want to worry about f3 coming with tempi followed by e4, so he takes prophylactic decision @@StartBracket@@pre-emptively@@EndBracket@@ retreating the knight. }
8... Nf6 9. O-O d6 10. Ng3 Nc6
{ White has to go for a basic 'space taking' plan. } 11. e4 Ne7
{ At first glance, it might look like not much to be going on as it is not obvious how  White can build further on his central pawn advance.  The problem for Black is that, well, White does have more space and side with more space @@StartBracket@@provided no direct reasons@@EndBracket@@ usually finds it easier to improve the position. I went for a 'standard Saemish rook lift'.   Positions type  11...fxe4  12.Nxe4  Nxe4  13.Bxe4  are better for White  @@StartBracket@@nice bishop pair, Black's e-pawn being a weakness@@EndBracket@@. }
12. Ra2 c5 13. Re2 Bd7 14. Rfe1
{ The last three moves and  White's position already significantly improved! e-file is important and White is ready to open it any moment, meanwhile Black struggles to find counterplay. }
14... Rc8 15. exf5 Nxf5 16. Nxf5 exf5 17. d5
{ I was thinking in the  direction of the Benoni type structures and that space advantage, e-file control ...should work to my favour.   Direct and strong was  17.Bf4!  Qb6  18.Qb1+-  and Black loses material. }
17... Rc7 { White is better but it is not easy to breakthrough. } 18. Qc2
{ Probably best for White was to press Black on the  d6  weakness with  18.Bf4  Bc8  and now takes space on kingside  19.h4  it is not clear as to what Black should do, as in the case of  19...h6  20.Bc2  White has exchange sacrifice ideas  20...Re8   20...Nh5  does not create any counterplay as Black remains tied up defending d6-weakness  21.Bh2  21.Re6!  Bxe6  22.dxe6  and Black's position soon collapses  22...g6  23.Ba4 }
18... Nh5 19. Bd2 h6 20. f3 b6 21. a4
{ This can be an unpleasant plan for Black in similar positions, as Black does not want to allow White to push a5 while pushing ...a5 himself creates b6-pawn weakness. }
21... Qf6 22. Qa2 a5 { 22...g5⇆  was principled and needed. } 23. Qb1
{ Now Black has too many weaknesses to defend. } 23... Rb7 24. Re7
{ @@StartBracket@@ 25.R1e6 is a threat@@EndBracket@@ } 24... Rf7 25. Rxf7 Qxf7
{ Now White wins a pawn. } 26. g4 Nf6 27. Bxf5 Bxf5 28. Qxf5 Re7 29. Rxe7
{ Perhaps even stronger was  29.Re6+- } 29... Qxe7 30. Kf2
{ White is a sound pawn up. White advances his kingside pawns, while also black d6-pawn is a weakness. Black's only chance is 'miracle draw' by perpetual check in a queen endgame. }
30... Qe8 31. g5 hxg5 32. Bxg5 Qxa4 33. Bxf6 gxf6
{ White has to pay attention, but there is no real 'perpetual check' danger and this queen ending is easily won. }
34. Qg6+ Kh8 35. Qxf6+ Kh7 36. Qe7+ Kh8 37. Qxd6 Qc2+ 38. Kg3 Qxc3
{ White's d-pawn is very fast, Black's king is weak, so there is no danger of any pawn race. }
39. Qf8+ Kh7 40. d6 Qe5+ 41. Kg4 Qd4+ 42. f4 a4
{ In the case of  42...Qg1+  Black quickly runs out of checks  43.Kf5  Qb1+  44.Kf6  Qg6+  45.Ke5 }
43. Qf7+ Kh6 44. d7
{ Black cannot prevent White from queening, while Black's a-pawn is still far from promotion. }
44... a3 45. Qf8+ Kg6 46. Qg8+ Kh6 47. Qg5+ Kh7 48. d8=Q Qg1+ 49. Kf5 Qb1+ 50.
Kf6 *

