[Black "Game 5: Sokolov, Ivan vs. Adams, Michael, Reykjavik, 2003"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 d5 6. cxd5 exd5
{ I have included this game as one may wonder what happens if White first develops his bishop to g5 and then plays e3 in this position. Well in that case Black gets an excellent Ragozin. This old game of Botvinnik turned into a disaster for White. Rare disaster @@StartBracket@@playing White@@EndBracket@@ for Botvinnik. }
7. Bg5 c5 8. f3
{ White wants to build @@StartBracket@@like in a regular Saemisch line 7. e3 c5 8. f3 @@EndBracket@@, but now @@StartBracket@@with White's bishop already developed to g5@@EndBracket@@ the e3 square will be vulnerable.   In the case of  8.Nf3  easiest for Black is to enter 'good Ragozin type positions' with  8...Nbd7  9.e3  Qa5  10.Qc2  Ne4  with Black having an excellent game.   In the case of  8.e3  best for Black is  8...Qa5!   8...h6  leads likely to a slight plus for White after  9.Bxf6  Qxf6  10.Bd3  O-O  11.Ne2⩲   Closing the center with  8...c4  @@StartBracket@@in order to prevent Bd3 development@@EndBracket@@ leads to some opening advantage for White after  9.Ne2  Nbd7   9...h6?  is a blunder since after  10.Bxf6  Qxf6  11.Nf4  Qd6  12.Qf3  Black loses material  12...Be6  13.Bxc4  dxc4  14.Qxb7  Qc6  15.Qxc6+  Nxc6  16.d5±  10.Ng3  h6  11.Bf4⩲  9.Ne2  this development @@StartBracket@@ the knight on e2 blocks the bishop on f1 @@EndBracket@@ does not look good for White  9...Ne4  10.Bf4  Nc6  11.Qc1  Black can go for a typical Ragozin motif  11...g5!  White's best is  12.f3  and after  12...gxf4  13.fxe4  dxe4  best for White is to sacrifice a pawn with  14.Nxf4  and after   14.d5  Ne5  15.Nxf4  Bf5  with castle queenside and good position for Black.  14...cxd4  15.exd4  Nxd4  probably White has compensation for equality  16.Bc4   Or  16.Rb1 }
8... h6 9. Bxf6
{ Keeping the bishop by playing  9.Bh4?!  is not good for White, because Black is faster with development and gains advantage  9...O-O  10.e3  Re8  White has problems here  11.Bf2  Black has better chances in the case of   11.Qd2  Nc6   11...c4⩱  12.Bb5  Qb6  13.a4  Nd7  14.Ne2  Na5  with ...c4, ...a6 to follow.  Nc6  White has problems developing his bishop on f1  12.Ne2  Bf5∓ }
9... Qxf6 10. e3 O-O
{ Due to the e3-pawn weakness, White cannot castle and has to place his king to f2-square. }
11. Ne2
{ The other way for White to develop  (similar to the game was)   11.Bd3  Re8  12.Kf2  Black is @@StartBracket@@like in the game@@EndBracket@@ probably well advised to develop his knight to c6-square  12...Nc6  13.Ne2  Bd7  with a pleasant position for Black. }
11... Re8 12. Kf2
{ Black decides to develop his knight to f6-square @@StartBracket@@which will give White some tactical possibilities related to g4, h4-pawns push@@EndBracket@@. }
12... Qe7 { 12...Nc6  was another option. } 13. Qd2 Nd7 14. Nf4 Nf6 15. Bd3 Bd7
{ Critical position! Strange enough, a player of Botvinnik's stature @@StartBracket@@and normally very strong in this type positions@@EndBracket@@ comes up with a completely wrong plan here! White needs to play on the kingside here and for a better or worse go for g4, h4 pawns push! }
16. h3
{ In the case of  16.h4  Black needs to react well  16...h5!  Black has stopped White g4-pawn push, but on the other hand Black no longer has ...g5-pawn push himself to destabilise White's knight. Position is about equal.   'Automatic type' move like  16...Rac8?  is a terrible mistake as after  17.g4+-  White suddenly has a crushing attack. Piece sacrifice  17...Bxg4  not saving Black as White wins after  18.fxg4  Nxg4+  19.Kf3+-  17.a4=   16.g4!?  was an interesting option, @@StartBracket@@again@@EndBracket@@ demanding good reaction from Black! In order to keep the balance Black has to sacrifice a piece @@StartBracket@@well...not exactly 'sacrifice' as Black gets many pawns for it@@EndBracket@@  16...Bxg4   In a similar positions ideas like  16...g5  sometimes works for Black, but not here as White is better after  17.Ng2±  with  h4  to follow   In the case of  16...Qd6  White continues with  17.Rae1↑  with h4 to follow  17.fxg4  Nxg4+  18.Kf3  Qh4  the position is sharp, mutually precise play is required  19.Rae1  g5!  20.h3!  Nxe3  21.Rxe3  Qxf4+  22.Ke2  White runs with his king to the queenside, while Black collects one more pawn  22...cxd4  23.cxd4  Qg3!  24.Re1  Qxh3  25.Kd1=  not easy to assess the position. My engine gives zeros. }
16... Qd6 17. Rhb1
{ This is clearly a step in the wrong direction!   17.g4!  was needed and after  17...Re7  18.Rae1  Rae8  19.Rhg1  @@StartBracket@@White wants 20.h4@@EndBracket@@ Black's best is most probably to force a draw with  19...g5!  20.Ng2  Ne4+!  21.fxe4  dxe4  and a draw by perpetual check.  22.Bb1  Qf6+  23.Kg3  Qd6+= }
17... b6
{ Black wants to play it safe. An alternative was   17...c4  18.Bc2   18.Bf1  loses to  18...g5!  @@StartBracket@@as I already have mentioned, this move often works for Black in similar positions@@EndBracket@@  19.Ne2  Qh2-+  18...Re7  and should White take a pawn?  19.Rxb7  but Black has probably more than 'just a compensation' after  19...g5!  20.Ne2  Rae8↑ }
18. Bf1
{ This bishop retreat should have run into an immediate refutation. Best for White was still to change his mind and go for  18.g4! }
18... Re7
{ Strong for Black was  18...g5-+  and Black has winning advantage  19.Ne2   19.Nd3  Qh2-+  Qh2  20.Ng1  Re6-+  White's position soon to collapse }
19. a4
{ Strange absence of feeling for danger! White could have stayed in the game with  19.dxc5!  Qxc5   19...bxc5  20.c4  20.Qd4 }
19... Rae8
{ Again strong for Black was  19...g5   Or even better  19...c4-+  with ...g5 to follow }
20. Re1
{ Last chance to stay in the game was  20.dxc5  bxc5  now White has tactical defense  21.e4!  Rxe4  22.Nxd5!  Bc6  23.Nxf6+  Qxf6  24.Kg1  Black is better, but White might survive. }
20... c4 { Now the game is over, 21...g5! being a terrible threat! } 21. g4
{ This move does not help White any longer. } 21... g5
{ White loses material. } 22. Ne2 { Or  22.Ng2  Qh2-+ } 22... Rxe3 23. Ng3
{ 23.Qxe3  loses to  23...Qh2+  24.Bg2  Rxe3  25.Kxe3  Qxg2-+ } 23... Qxg3+ 24.
Kxg3 Ne4+ { terrible defeat for Botvinnik! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Game 6: Botvinnik, Mikhail Moisevich vs. Kotov, Alexander, Groningen, 1946"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ I have selected this game to help the reader understand better the kind of positions we can get in the Saemisch.The strategic plan that Black has chosen in this game, is NOT advisable with our move order. }
4. e3
{ Our move order is  4.a3  Bxc3+  5.bxc3  O-O  6.f3!  @@StartBracket@@not 6.e3 as in this game@@EndBracket@@ and now if Black follows the e-pawn push plan with  6...d6   Or  6...Re8  7.e4  e5  8.Bd3  with Ne2 to follow.  7.e4  e5  8.Bd3  with Ne2 to follow. Black has no counterplay as in the game with the e4-advance, while now it is also too late to play on White's c4-pawn weakness. }
4... O-O 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3
{ Now with the white pawn on e3, Black can decide for the e-pawn push plan. }
6... Re8 7. Ne2 e5 8. Ng3 d6
{ White needs to develop his Bf1. Should he develop it to d3 or e2? } 9. Be2
{ Probably the most precise for White!   We have an interesting game with the development of the bishop on the d3-square.  9.Bd3  e4!  Black correctly takes space.  10.Bb1  b6  Black is quick to hit White on his weakness on c4, while White is quick with his central counterplay.  11.f3!  Ba6!  Black follows on his plan.   11...Bb7  Aiming to maintain the status quo in the centre does not work for Black, as White will increase the pressure on the f-file and then open the centre on his own terms with fxe4.  12.Ra2!  Nbd7  13.O-O  with Raf2 to follow.  12.fxe4  Bxc4  13.Qf3  Nbd7  We have an interesting position! White has a strong pawn centre, however he has problems developing his rook and white's king, being prevented from castling, is also a problem. White comes up with an inventive solution!  14.Ra2!  Bxa2  Black accepts the sacrifice.   My Stockfish 14 gives as Black's best to keep his strong bishop, thus preventing White from castling kingside, and opt for  14...g6!  Not exactly an easy move for a human, not having the dark square bishop to protect the king.  15.Rf2  Qe7  To me it seems a complicated and sharp position, my engine says: 'Black stands better'.  15.Bxa2  Nf8  For a sacrificed exchange, White can now solve all the problems related to his king's position.  16.O-O  Ng6  17.Bd2  White has a strong mobile pawn center, pressure over the f-file and a potentially very powerful pair of bishops.In a human play, White has full compensation.  17...Qd7   17...Kh8!?  Is the computer's proposal.  18.Bxf7  Rf8  Black now gets counterplay.  18.Nf5  Qd8?  This time loss allows White to display his attacking skills! Now White uses his mobile pawn center to open the position for his powerful bishops!   Black had a defense in  18...Rxe4  19.Nxg7  Nf4!  White now needs to be precise with  20.Ne6!  fxe6  21.exf4  d5  22.Bb1  Rf8∞  A strange position, with the black rook blocked on square e4; the engine evaluation gives zero.   18...Nxe4??  leads to disaster after the simple  19.Bxf7+  Kxf7  20.Nh6+  Ke7  21.Qxe4++-  19.e5!  dxe5  20.e4!  exd4  Black actually does not have much of a choice.  21.Nxg7!  White's handling of the attack is a textbook example!  21...Ne5   21...Re5  loses to the simple  22.Nf5   21...Kxg7  loses to  22.Bg5+-  22.Qh3  dxc3  23.Bxc3  Kxg7  24.Qg3+  Ng6  White now hurried to regain the lost material. Better was simply to increase the pressure with  25.Qg5  White collects black Nf6 for free and continues with his crushing attack.   25.Bxf6+  Qxf6  26.Rxf6  Kxf6  27.h4  and White went on to win in Kaidanov,G @@StartBracket@@2616@@EndBracket@@ -Onischuk,A @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ Chicago 2002.  25...h6  26.Bxf6+  Kh7  27.Qg4  and Black's position collapses in a few moves. }
9... Nbd7
{ Black would have done better to push his pawn onto e4-square and take up space, either on this move or the next.   For example  9...e4!  and the play may continue  10.O-O   Trying to take advantage of the moment with  10.f3  b6  11.fxe4?!  does not work well for White, as Black has a strong positional pawn sacrifice.  11...Nxe4!   11...Bb7  is wrong due to  12.e5!  dxe5  13.O-O  Nbd7  14.Bd3  and White doubles on the f-file getting a strong attack.  12.Nxe4  Rxe4  13.O-O   13.Bf3?  Bg4  is better for Black.  13...Nd7  14.Bd3   14.Bf3  offers Black an extra option in  14...Nf6  14...Bb7∞  White is not forced to take the black rook and can delay the decision.  15.Ra2  Qe7  16.Raf2  Rf8  If White takes the black rook, Black will have great compensation. White can ignore the black rook on e4, but it is not clear how he can proceed.  10...Nbd7  11.Ra2  b6  12.f3  Bb7  White should probably decide on a different kingside strategy.  13.f4!  Black wants to be able to take his bishop to a6 undisturbed.  13...a5  14.Nh1!  White has good attacking prospects on the kingside.  14...h5   14...Ba6  15.g4  15.Bd2 }
10. O-O c5
{ It is surprising to see a player of Keres' stature make such a positional error.   10...e4!  was needed for a transposition to the previous comment. }
11. f3
{ Black is now in a bad situation. White will push e4 thus building a strong centre, while Black does not have his regular counterplay. Realizing that things have gone wrong Keres tries to create something. }
11... cxd4
{ The situation was bad, this attempt at counterplay will only accelerate the process. }
12. cxd4 Nb6 13. Bb2 exd4 14. e4
{ Typical situation that Black must avoid! White has a strong bishop on b2 and a strong centre, he has excellent prospects of attacking the black king. Finally, the weakness of the d6 pawn is much more worrying than the potential weakness on c4. }
14... Be6 15. Rc1
{ Choosing between bad possibilities is always a terrible task. The rest of the game will be quick. }
15... Re7 { 15...Rc8  16.Qxd4  looks bad for Black as well. } 16. Qxd4
{ Black has no time for  16...Rc7  , as White wants  17.Rfd1  winning the d6-pawn. }
16... Qc7 17. c5 dxc5 18. Rxc5 Qf4 19. Bc1
{ Engine gives as strongest  19.Bb5  the point being that Black will have problems with his queen.  19...Nbd7   19...Bd7  runs into  20.Nf5+-  20.Ne2  Qh4  21.g3+-  Qh3  22.Nf4  Qh6  and White has many ways to win. }
19... Qb8
{ White ends the game with a mating attack.   More stubborn was  19...Rd7  but will only prolong the inevitable  20.Qa1  Qd6  21.Be3+- }
20. Rg5 Nbd7 21. Rxg7+ Kxg7 22. Nh5+ Kg6
{ Or  22...Kg8  23.Nxf6+  Nxf6  24.Qxf6 } 23. Qe3 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Game 7 : Botvinnik, Mikhail Moisevich vs. Averbakh, Yuri, Moscow, 1956"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Nc6
{ This was a training game, published something like thirty years later in the book Botvinnik's Secret Games. The idea is very inventive.White sacrifices a pawn and also allows Black to deprive him of castling to open diagonals for his bishops. Unfortunately the idea doesn't work. Black has a rather convincing refutation. }
8. e4
{ The main line is considered to be  8.Ne2  b6  9.e4  Ne8  10.O-O  Ba6  11.f4  f5  etc. }
8... cxd4 9. cxd4 { An important moment! } 9... Nxd4
{ White's refutation of the opening idea is somewhat surprising.  9...d5!  Black helps White to improve his central pawn chain. Unfortunately for White the tactics works for Black. Botvinnik probably underestimated the tactical element and too quickly drew the conclusion White is doing well.  10.cxd5   10.e5?  blunders into  10...dxc4  11.Bxc4  Qxd4!  exd5  11.e5  Ne4  White does not have a good move here and has to choose between different ways to stand worse, e.g.  12.Ne2   Or  12.Be3  Qa5+  13.Kf1  f6  12...Bg4  13.Be3   13.f3??  blunders into  13...Bxf3-+  14.gxf3  Qh4+  Qa5+  14.Kf1  f6  Black has a better development, White cannot maintain his central pawn chain. The only thing we can discuss here is the size of Black's advantage. }
10. e5 Qa5+ 11. Kf1 Ne8 { 11...Qxe5??  blunders a piece to prosaic  12.Bb2 }
12. Bb2
{ White is playing for the initiative.   White is not interested in getting his pawn back because after  12.Bxh7+  Kxh7  13.Qxd4  f6  only Black can be better. }
12... Nc6 13. Nf3
{ The position Botvinnik was probably aiming for! For his sacrificed pawn White gained a development advantage. White's uncastled king on f1 should not be a problem  @@StartBracket@@as we shall soon see white rooks will take the e- and g-files@@EndBracket@@. The position looks promising for White; Black must watch out for the textbook Bxh7 sacrifice. }
13... f5
{ Arguably the most logical, but not the best!   13...f6!  The best of silicon brain for Black, and after  14.Qc2  h6  15.Nh4  From a human perspective White seems to have a strong attack, but the silicon brain is not afraid of ghosts and courageously continues  15...Nxe5!  16.Bh7+  Kh8!  White has to go for an exchange win.  17.Bxe5   17.f4?  loses to  17...Nxc4  fxe5  18.Ng6+  Kxh7  19.Nxf8+  Kg8  20.Ng6  Nf6  And now probably White's best is  21.h4  This position does not seem clear to me, but Stockfish 14 prefers Black. }
14. Qc2 d6 15. Re1
{ Now the idea behind Botvinnik's pawn sacrifice becomes clear. White is harmoniously developed and will push g4 by attacking the black king. }
15... dxe5 16. Nxe5 Nf6 17. h3
{ this move @@StartBracket@@preparing g4-push@@EndBracket@@ was not neccessary!   The immediate  17.g4!  was strong and in a human game, White probably has more than just compensation. Black can easily lose, for example  17...fxg4?   The engine calmly defends with  17...Qc7!  18.Rg1  Nxe5  19.Rxe5  Bd7!  20.gxf5  Rae8!  it is not easy for a human to display this 'calm defense'.  21.fxe6  Rxe6  22.Bxh7+  Kh8  And as usual with many engine lines, the evaluation is zeros :-@@EndBracket@@  18.h3!  g3  19.Rg1!  White has winning attack.  19...gxf2  losing to the prosaic  20.Bxh7+  Kh8   20...Nxh7?  runs into a mate in three:  21.Rxg7+  Kxg7  22.Qg6+  Kh8  23.Nf7  21.Ng6+  Kxh7  22.Nxf8+  Kg8  23.Qxf2  and Black is mated in a few moves. }
17... Qc5
{ Instead of developing, Black is losing time.   Best was  17...Nxe5!  18.Rxe5  Qc7  19.g4  Bd7  White at most has enough compensation for equality, but certainly not more. }
18. g4 Ne4 19. Nxc6 Qxc6 20. Rg1 { Black has to protect the g7-square. } 20...
Rf7
{ White gets ready to double his rooks @@StartBracket@@once g-file is open@@EndBracket@@ . }
21. Re3 { White has a strong attack, but Black should not lose. } 21... Qc5
{ A losing mistake.   Black could have saved the game with the calm  21...Kf8!  The point being that the pawn on g7 will not hang with check, e.g.  22.gxf5   Objectively best for White is  22.Bxe4  fxe4  23.Qxe4=  exf5  23.Bxe4  fxe4  24.Qc3  And now Black has  24...Be6!  25.Rxg7  Qxc4+  26.Kg2  Qxc3  27.Rxf7+  Kxf7  28.Rxc3  though Black is a pawn up, a draw is the most likely result. }
22. gxf5 { Now the game is over, as Black cannot defend his g7-pawn. } 22...
exf5 23. Bxe4 fxe4 24. Qc3 *

