[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 Nc6 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 b6 7. e4 Ba6 8. Bg5
{ 8.Bd3  I have recommended in this course.   8.e5  taking immediate action is another often played move in this position - see Kotov-Keres in this games section. }
8... h6 9. Bh4
{ Magnus now goes for an  interesting idea @@StartBracket@@almost a novelty@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Qc8
{ Black moves away from the h4-d8 diagonal pin and is ready for the 'standard Saemisch' ...Qb7-...Qc6 plan targeting White's c4-pawn.   Black's main moves in this position were considered to be  9...Na5   or  9...g5  both moves Magnus faced sitting on the white side of the  Saemisch. }
10. Bd3
{ Pawn structure damage  10.Bxf6  gxf6  proof of a rather 'academic nature' as after  11.Nh3  Na5  12.Nf4  h5  White finds it difficult to target black kingside pawns, while white c4-pawn weakness is an imminent worry. }
10... Na5
{ Facing a novel plan, Wesley takes a logical/practical decision - 'develop the queen, defend the pawn and then decide'. }
11. Qe2
{ This game was an internet rapid game and Magnus probably did not want to spend too much time at an early stage of the game @@StartBracket@@though crises in the Saemisch often come early!@@EndBracket@@.    (In one of the very few games we have)   with @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/p1pp1pp1/bpn1pn1p/8/2PPP2B/P1P2P2/6PP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qc8  move   White went for a less logical way to defend his c4-pawn weakness  11.Qa4  Black continued with  11...c5   Following on the standard Black's plan with  11...Qb7  @@StartBracket@@intending12...Qc6 @@EndBracket@@ forces White to push  12.d5  after which White's position starts to look a bit 'over-extended.  12.Bxf6  gxf6  in order not to @@StartBracket@@immediately@@EndBracket@@ lose the c4-pawn White's next move is forced  13.d5  Qc7  14.Ne2  O-O-O  15.f4?  White is not ready for this central pawn push here. Black now breaks White's center with the thematic  White's best move is  (probably)   15.O-O  though Black has a pleasant  @@StartBracket@@probably better@@EndBracket@@ position after  15...Rdg8  starting to prepare threats on the kingside.  White would love to trade the knights to release the pressure on his c4-pawn, but   15.Nc1?  @@StartBracket@@intending 16.Nb3 @@EndBracket@@ does not work due to simple  15...Qe5-+  15...f5!  White now loses @@StartBracket@@at least@@EndBracket@@ a pawn  16.e5  d6!  17.exd6  Rxd6  18.O-O-O  Qd7  the most practical. White has to trade queens and Black gets easily won endgame  19.Qxd7+  Rxd7  20.dxe6  fxe6  21.Ng3  Bxc4  Black is a sound pawn up plus a  great position and soon won in Raineri de Luca,P @@StartBracket@@2350@@EndBracket@@-Moskalenko,V  @@StartBracket@@2544@@EndBracket@@ Barbera del Valles 2004.   It is good to mention that Ukrainian GM Viktor Moskalenko is a 'Saemisch white side expert' and his going as Black for @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/p1pp1pp1/bpn1pn1p/8/2PPP2B/P1P2P2/6PP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qc8!  is certainly worth taking notice of!  It is not a thankful task to give White advice as to how to combat 9...Qc8! One possible way can be   11.e5!?  and we may get some crazy tactical mess!  11...Nh5  White does not give Black the time to conveniently grab on c4  12.Nh3!  @@StartBracket@@threat is 13. f4 @@EndBracket@@  12...g5  who cares, White pushes it anyway!  13.f4!  gxh4  14.Qxh5  Black now better hurries up with castling queenside @@StartBracket@@bringing his king to safety@@EndBracket@@  14...Qb7!  15.Ng5  O-O-O  16.Be4  Black's position looks bad, but he keeps the dynamic balance with queen sacrifice!  16...hxg5!!  17.Bxb7+  Bxb7  18.Qe2  h3  this position @@StartBracket@@for a human@@EndBracket@@ in OTB play almost impossible to evaluate. My Stockfish 14 says 'zeros'! }
11... d6
{ This decision should have had put Black in serious trouble! White takes a strong and principled straightforward decision.   Immediate  11...Qb7!  was Black's best. Black has tactical threat 12...Bxc4. I have failed to find an advantage for White. In one practical test we have, White sacrificed or blundered a pawn on c4 @@StartBracket@@allowing Black to execute his threat@@EndBracket@@  12.f4?  Bxc4!  13.Bxf6   On  13.Bxc4  Black responds with  13...Qc6  getting his piece back and remaining a pawn up.  Bxd3  14.Qxd3  gxf6  White does not have @@StartBracket@@nearly@@EndBracket@@ enough compensation for his sacrificed/blundered pawn, though he managed to confuse matters eventually emerging victorious in Berczes, D @@StartBracket@@2450@@EndBracket@@-Jaracz, P @@StartBracket@@2488@@EndBracket@@ Zalakaros 2006 }
12. f4 { White's center has started to roll and looks scary. } 12... Qd7
{ Critical moment! Obviously, Wesley did consider immediately to push 13. e5, but being a rapid game, he could not fully calculate it and did not want to spend too much time on it, so he took a seemingly 'clever practical' decision - 'first develop knight and then evaluate e5-pawn push'. This decision will prove to be a serious mistake! }
13. Nf3
{ At first glance White seems to be doing great. His knight has just been developed and he is about to start his 'crushing central pawns roll'.  Magnus finds a beautiful resource!   Immediate  13.e5!  was needed and Black is in big trouble!  13...Nh7  14.Nh3!  White will continue with his pawns roll, while Black does not have a good way to react   Material greed  14.Bxh7?  Rxh7  15.Qe4  runs into a nice refutation  15...Qc6!  16.Qxh7  Qxg2  White has quite a number of checks, however black king safely runs to the queenside!  17.Qg8+  Kd7  18.Qxf7+  Kc6  19.d5+  Kb7  20.exd6  now Black imposes deadly threats while vacating a6-square for his king  20...Bxc4!  and Black wins, as White either gets mated or suffers decisive material loses.  14...Qa4   14...Qc6  does not save Black too after  15.d5!   15.f5  here does not work well  15...Bxc4  16.fxe6  O-O  ∞  with an unclear game, White can become worse too...for example  17.e7  Rfe8  18.exd6?!  Bxd3  19.Qxd3  Qxd6  20.O-O  f6⩱  exd5  White can force superior endgame  16.exd6+  Silicon brain gives as White's best   16.O-O  O-O  17.Qc2!  and White wins.  Kf8  17.Qe7+  Kg8  18.Qxc7  Black's best here is to enter bad endgame  18...Bxc4  19.Qxc6  Nxc6  20.Bxc4  dxc4  21.O-O-O  ±  with precise play, White should win.  15.f5  Black here cannot solve problem of his weak king, e.g.  15...Bxc4   15...exf5  16.exd6++-   15...O-O  loses to  16.f6  16.fxe6  arguably best for Black is  16...O-O  however after   16...fxe6  17.O-O  castling is prevented and black king cannot escape into safety. Checks are going to start and White either wins in attack or wins decisive material.  17.e7  Rfe8  18.exd6  cxd6  19.O-O  White has winning attack. }
13... Nh5 14. g3
{ On the surface, White's position still looks great, but Black has a beautiful pawn sacrifice turning the tables!  White's  (objectively)  best was   14.Bg3  accepting somewhat worse position after  14...O-O-O  ⩱ }
14... g5 15. fxg5 hxg5 16. Nxg5
{ Now point behind 13...Nh5! becomes clear.   16.Bxg5??  blunders into prosaic  16...Nxg3 }
16... Nf4 17. gxf4 Rxh4
{ White, technically still a pawn up is saddled with a weak king and plenty of weak pawns. In a higher sense, the game has been decided! }
18. Qf2 Rh8
{ Understanding he has a terribly weak king, Wesley hopes a queen trade will bring him closer to a draw. }
19. f5 O-O-O 20. fxe6 fxe6 21. Qf7 Rdg8 22. Qxd7+ Kxd7
{ Sadly for White, the queen swap did not change anything. White still has a weak king and plenty of weak pawns.  Magnus executes with a steady hand. }
23. Nf3 Rh3 24. Kf2 Rf8
{ Next to starting to lose material, White is also under multiple pins. } 25.
Be2 Bxc4 26. Raf1 Rf4 27. Ke3 e5 { White is completely tied up } 28. dxe5 dxe5
29. Rhg1 { Time for Black to collect some material } 29... Bxe2 30. Kxe2 Rxe4+
31. Kf2 Nc4
{ Black is having  a decisive material advantage plus a better position } 32.
Rg3
{ Black is the attacking side and of course keeps all four rooks on the board. }
32... Rh6 33. a4 { Now comes a typical Carlsen move. } 33... a5
{ Black has all the time in the world. } 34. Rfg1 Rf4
{ White hopes to run away from pins. } 35. Kg2 { But now after } 35... Ne3+ 36.
Kh1 Nf5 { White loses a piece. } 37. Nxe5+ Ke6 38. Rg4 Rf2 *

