[Black "Game 9 : Bronstein, David Ionovich vs. Simagin, Vladimir Pavlovich, Moscow ,1961"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 Nf6 2. d4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5 6. f3
{ This old idea of Bronstein's has been applied relatively recently in a top game in a different variant of the Nimzo Saemisch.   6.e3  Nc6  7.Bd3  O-O  8.Ne2  b6  9.e4  Ne8  10.O-O  Ba6  11.f4  f5  12.d5  Na5  This is a well-known position. White, following Bronstein's idea, sacrifices his c4 pawn to push his d pawn to d6 and block black's Ng7.  13.e5!  Bxc4   13...d6!  stopping White's idea is, in my opinion, Black's best response.  14.Bxc4  Nxc4  15.d6  and, just like in Broonstein's game, due to the fact that black Ne8 is out of play White has a strong compensation for the sacrificed pawn, as seen in Milov-J.Polgar, FIDE World Ch. K.O. 2001. }
6... Nc6 7. e4 O-O 8. e5
{ It is interesting that what, even according to modern engines, seems to be White's best line is something Bronstein played 60 years ago! }
8... Ne8 9. f4 cxd4
{ In the theory part I advised Black not to allow White to execute his idea and play  9...d5 }
10. cxd4 b6
{ Black is focused on the c4-pawn allowing the white d-pawn to advance. } 11.
Nf3 Ba6 12. Bd3
{ Threat is @@StartFEN@@r2qnrk1/p2p1ppp/bpn1p3/4P3/2PP1P2/P2B1N2/6PP/R1BQK2R w KQ - 3 12@@EndFEN@@  13.Bxh7 }
12... f5
{ 12...Na5??  falls to a well known elementary tactic  13.Bxh7+!  Kxh7  14.Ng5+  Kg6   Or  14...Kg8  15.Qh5  15.f5+   15.Qg4  should win as well  exf5  16.g4  and White soon wins. }
13. d5 Na5 14. d6 Rc8 15. O-O g6
{ The knight on e8 has no chance to escape from his 'prison on the crown side', so white wants as quickly as possible to open the queenside and win the game there. }
16. c5
{ The most principled, though your engine will say 'no need to hurry' and will give many moves leading to a White's clear advantage. }
16... Bxd3 17. Qxd3 Rxc5 18. Be3 Rd5 19. Qa6 Nc6
{ White is not a pawn down, but rather a piece up and is ready to sacrifice material to break through. }
20. Rfc1 { Black wants to be able to put his Rf8 into play. } 20... Ng7 21.
Rxc6 { Black was facing a difficult decision. } 21... Ra5
{ This allows a nice queen sacrifice.   21...dxc6  22.Qxa7  c5  offered a better chance of survival, although the position remains difficult. }
22. Qxa5
{ In the resulting position the white rook would be devastatingly strong on the 7th rank. On top of that the black knight remains out of play, so it is fair to say that it is actually white who has a material advantage. }
22... bxa5 23. Rc7 h6 { Hoping to push g5 creating some sort of counterplay. }
24. Rb1 Ne8 25. Rxa7
{ Black goes for his only chance, hoping for some 'miraculous counterplay'. }
25... g5 26. Bb6
{ Winning the d7-pawn.   The simple  26.Rbb7  was winning too. } 26... Qb8
{ 26...Qc8  runs into  27.Bc7  with Rb8 to follow and Black loses his queen. }
27. Rxd7
{ The important pawn on d7 is lost, while Black is far from any counterplay. }
27... Qc8 28. Re7 Qc2 29. Rf1 Qc6 30. Bf2 Ng7
{ Black hopes to finally bring his knight into play. White calmly collects more material. }
31. fxg5 hxg5 32. Nxg5 Qd5 33. Nf3
{ The white knight was well placed on  g5  , even better was  33.Re1  Re8  34.Rc7+- }
33... f4 34. Rc7 Nf5
{ The black knight is finally in play, but black is still far from creating a serious counterplay. White, however, must play with precision and Bronstein executes with a steady hand. }
35. Rb1 Ne3 36. h3 { As we shall see - a smart move. } 36... Qd3 37. Rbc1 Nd5
{ 37...Qg6  does not work due to  38.Bxe3  fxe3  39.R1c4!  Good that 36.h3! has been played. White ends having an easily won rook endgame.  39...Rxf3   39...Qb1+  loses after  40.Kh2  e2  41.Rg4+  Kh8  42.d7!  e1=Q  43.Nxe1  Qxe1  44.Rg5!  The most precise.   The simple  44.Rc8  Qxe5+  45.Rg3  Qd6  46.Re8  wins as well.  44...Qe3  45.Rc8  Qf4+  46.Rg3  Kh7  47.Re8  and White queens.  40.Rg4  Qxg4  41.hxg4  e2  the following sequence of moves is more or less forced.  42.Rc1  Re3  43.Kf2  Rxe5  44.d7  e1=Q+  45.Rxe1  Rd5  46.Rxe6  Rxd7  47.Re5  and this rook ending, due to the a-pawns, is easily won for White. }
38. R7c6 { White wants to push d7. } 38... Ne3
{ White knocks out the black knight and wins another pawn in the process. } 39.
R6c3 Qb5 { Or  39...Qe4  40.Re1  with Bxe3 to follow. } 40. Bxe3 fxe3 41. Rxe3
Qb6 42. Rc3
{ The position is resignable for Black, as he is unable to create any counterplay, while his king is becoming a target. }
42... Kg7 43. Kh2 Kh6 44. Re4 Qb2 { Black resigned. } *

