8... Ng8 9. Nh3
{ Regular square for the knight in these positions.The Knight can later jump to g5@@StartBracket@@or f2-e4@@EndBracket@@ or support bishop on g5. }
9... Na5
{ Black goes for his regular plan in these positions -hitting on white c4-pawn weakness. Not seeing an immediate way to attack on the kingside, White protects his c4-pawn. }
10. Qa4 Ne7
{ Black can also try on his regular plan to bring his queen to the c6-square, but here it does not work that well for Black   10...Qc8  11.Bd3  Qb7  now White provokes c6-move  12.Be4!  c6  13.Bd3  Qc7  14.O-O  and White has good attacking prospects Ng5-Ne4-Nd6 or Nf4-Nh5 being the ideas and should Black really insist on collecting white pawn on c4 with  14...c5  White happily sacrifices material  15.Ng5!  cxd4  16.Ne4!  Qxe5  17.f4  Qc7  18.f5  and White has strong attack @@StartBracket@@worth more than the sacrificed material@@EndBracket@@. }
11. Bd3
{ To castle or not? Difficult decision here. Castling prepares an unpleasant for White counterplay with d6, hitting the vulnerable white center. On the other hand, White is ready to attack and the king on g8 could prove to be an easy target. To decide for 11...O-O here needs strong nerves, however, the decision is not wrong as Black can fight White's attack off while hitting on White's center creating counterplay of his own! }
11... O-O
{ Delaying the castle and playing  11...h6!?  was also possible, however after  12.Nf4  with Nh5 to follow, the Black king is not safe either. }
12. Bg5
{ Another way to attack was  12.Ng5  in a 'human OTB play' we certainly have unclear game! Silicon brain is @@StartBracket@@of course@@EndBracket@@ not afraid, collects material and likes Black!  12...h6  White's best is  13.Nh7!  White's attack looks dangerous, however my engine calmly proposes two way for Black here   13.Bh7+?!  Kh8  14.h4  does not work for White due to  14...Bxc4  White has to try to 'build a B+Q battery'  15.Bb1  to start with Black has a draw in his pocket  15...Bb3  16.Qb5  Bc4  17.Qa4  but should play for more!  17...f5!  18.exf6  Rxf6  19.Qc2  Nf5  and White is not in time, as  20.g4  loses to  20...Nb3  and White cannot keep his 'attacking Q+B battery' intact.  21.Ra2  Nxc1  13...Bxc4  Or   13...Re8  14.Bxh6  gxh6  15.Nf6+  Kh8  also saying Black to be better.  14.Bxc4  Kxh7  White should now build 'Q+B battery'  15.Qc2+  Kg8  16.Ba2  engine calmly starts counterplay on the queenside  16...c5  and after  17.Bb1  defends with  17...Ng6  18.h4  Re8  19.h5  Nf8  and says 'Black opens up on the queenside, White's attack is not fast enough'. }
12... h6 13. Bh4
{ How to hit White's centre:  13...d5  or  13...d6  , what would you do? }
13... d5
{ A Strategic mistake, leaving White's central pawn chain intact. As expected, White sets up a 'Q+B battery'.   Black had to hit directly on White's pawn chain with  13...d6!  White's pawn center is about to collapse and White's only chance is 'Q+B battery', however, White is not in time  14.Bb1   In the case of  14.Rd1?  Black's task is easy as he plays  14...Qe8  and collects white c4-pawn.  dxe5  15.dxe5  now Black needs to be precise!   15.Qc2?  makes the job easy for Black after simple  15...f5-+  15...g5!  those kind of moves are not easy to play, however here works perfect for Black  16.Qc2   16.Nxg5  loses to  16...Nf5!  17.Bxf5  exf5  18.Rd1  Qe7  and black wins  Nf5  17.g4  Black now reminds White to have a weak king too and gets winning attack  17...Nxc4!  18.gxf5  Nxe5  and Black wins. White is now the one with the weak king and is also losing material. Note that play is very sharp and there is a rather thin line between winning and losing. }
14. Bb1
{ Now @@StartBracket@@thanks to his unchallenged central pawn chain@@EndBracket@@ White has enough time for attack! Just like in the previous comment, Black's only move is not really an easy-to-play one! Keres senses it correctly! }
14... g5
{ Some other moves like for example  14...Bxc4?  lead to a disaster after the simple  15.Qc2  g6  16.Bf6+-  and White has 'all the time in the World' to mate Black. }
15. Qc2 { Critical moment! } 15... Ng6
{ This seemingly 'natural move' turns out to be a losing mistake. How should White break through Black's defences?   Another knight jump  15...Nf5?  loses to prosaic  16.g4   Black however had an excellent resource here in  15...f5!!  16.exf6  and now  16...Nf5  as after  17.g4  Black can support the f5-square with  17...Qxf6  the position is razor sharp. Provided both sides' play the best moves, the position is likely dynamically balanced. White's next move is not an easy one  18.Rg1!   More logical may seem  18.gxf5  exf5  19.Nxg5  however now after  19...Rae8+!   19...hxg5?  20.Rg1  20.Kd1   In the case of  20.Kf2  Black is better after  20...Nxc4  21.Rg1  Kh8∓  Black will get his material back, while having safer king.  hxg5!   20...Nxc4  looks tempting, however with precise play White holds the balance  21.Rg1!  Ne3+  22.Kc1  Nxc2  now it cleans up into an ending  23.Nh3+!  Kf7  24.Bxf6  Nxa1  25.Be5  White has a double threat 26.Rg7+ or 26.Kb2 @@StartBracket@@trapping the knight@@EndBracket@@, so Black has to give @@StartBracket@@his extra@@EndBracket@@ exchenge back  25...Rxe5  26.dxe5  Nb3+  27.Kd1=∞  Black is a pawn up, White @@StartBracket@@looks like@@EndBracket@@ has enough compensation to hold the balance.  21.Rg1  and now Black should not be 'afraid of the ghosts' and calmly play  21...Bxc4!  and after  22.Bxg5   22.Rxg5+?  loses to    the simple  22...Qxg5  23.Bxg5  Bb3  Qe6∓  White does not have good discovered check.  Kh8   18...Rae8  leads to a move transposition after  19.Nxg5!  now Black needs to be careful!  19...Kh8!   19...hxg5  leads to White's advantage after  20.gxf5  exf5+  21.Kf2±  20.gxf5  exf5+  21.Kd1!  -see the main line.  19.gxf5  exf5  20.Nxg5  Rae8+  where to go with the king?  21.Kd1!   21.Kf2  Nxc4∓  Black will get his material back, while having safer king.  Nxc4  position is razor sharp, however  @@StartBracket@@most likely@@EndBracket@@ equal. The following line looks logical, leading to a perpetual check  22.Qf2  Ne3+  23.Kd2  Black brings extra attacking force on the queenside  23...Qc6!  24.Nh3!  Nc4+  25.Kd1  Ne3+  26.Kd2= }
